1
00:00:11,160 --> 00:00:13,083
(♪♪♪)

2
00:01:00,400 --> 00:01:05,247
<i>♪ You do something to me</i>

3
00:01:05,320 --> 00:01:10,247
<i>♪ Something that
simply mystifies me</i>

4
00:01:10,320 --> 00:01:15,042
<i>♪ Tell me,
why should it be</i>

5
00:01:15,120 --> 00:01:19,967
<i>♪ You have the power
to hypnotize me?</i>

6
00:01:20,040 --> 00:01:24,967
<i>♪ Let me live
'neath your spell</i>

7
00:01:25,040 --> 00:01:29,443
<i>♪ Do do that voodoo
that you do so well</i>

8
00:01:29,520 --> 00:01:34,082
<i>♪ 'Cause you do
something to me</i>

9
00:01:34,160 --> 00:01:38,051
<i>♪ That nobody else
could do ♪</i>

10
00:01:40,200 --> 00:01:42,771
(♪♪♪)

11
00:01:49,880 --> 00:01:51,530
(GROWLING)

12
00:01:53,400 --> 00:01:54,811
(♪♪♪)

13
00:02:31,080 --> 00:02:32,320
(CLAPS)

14
00:02:57,680 --> 00:02:59,808
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

15
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:43,811
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

16
00:03:43,880 --> 00:03:45,245
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

17
00:03:48,360 --> 00:03:51,443
MAN: Bravo! Bravo!

18
00:03:54,480 --> 00:03:57,609
I don't understand. ls the
conductor a blithering idiot?

19
00:03:57,680 --> 00:03:59,762
We went over
the tempo six times!

20
00:03:59,840 --> 00:04:02,923
It's adagio, adagio, adagio.
It's not racehorse tempo!

21
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:04,650
Ja, ja, Herr Crawford.
I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

22
00:04:04,720 --> 00:04:06,290
What? Don't be sorry!

23
00:04:06,360 --> 00:04:08,169
Get it right.
What good are apologies

24
00:04:08,240 --> 00:04:09,969
when the poetry of
the moment is lost?

25
00:04:10,040 --> 00:04:11,166
And you!
You're supposed to knock

26
00:04:11,240 --> 00:04:12,287
when you're
ready in the trunk.

27
00:04:12,360 --> 00:04:13,566
How do I know
when you're all clear?

28
00:04:13,640 --> 00:04:15,165
Well, I'm sorry, Mr. Crawford,
I couldn't breathe in that...

29
00:04:15,240 --> 00:04:16,810
Well, you're not hired
to breathe!

30
00:04:16,880 --> 00:04:18,370
But it was her first time,
Mr. Crawford.

31
00:04:18,440 --> 00:04:21,569
My God, we went over this
routine all afternoon.

32
00:04:21,640 --> 00:04:23,483
How do I know when to begin
sticking in the swords?

33
00:04:23,560 --> 00:04:25,164
I could have
stabbed you to death,

34
00:04:25,240 --> 00:04:27,049
and then,
I get blood on my ensemble.

35
00:04:27,160 --> 00:04:29,128
Oh, Mr. Wei Ling Soo! You
were, as always, brilliant!

36
00:04:29,200 --> 00:04:30,645
Oh, I've already
taken off my robe.

37
00:04:30,720 --> 00:04:31,801
MAN: Can my wife and I
take a photo of you?

38
00:04:31,880 --> 00:04:33,211
MAN 2:
An autograph, please?

39
00:04:33,280 --> 00:04:35,567
Autographs are for
mental defectives.

40
00:04:35,640 --> 00:04:37,051
But I want to prove
I met you.

41
00:04:37,120 --> 00:04:39,282
Well, if you don't mind, I'd
rather that proof didn't exist.

42
00:04:39,360 --> 00:04:41,681
What if you get
picked up for sodomy?

43
00:04:47,120 --> 00:04:48,645
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

44
00:04:48,720 --> 00:04:50,085
Yes!

45
00:04:50,160 --> 00:04:52,049
MAN: Stanley?

46
00:04:52,120 --> 00:04:53,326
Burkan!

47
00:04:53,400 --> 00:04:54,686
How are you, Howard?

48
00:04:54,760 --> 00:04:57,969
Brilliant. You are still
the best in the world.

49
00:04:58,040 --> 00:05:00,611
No thanks to the assorted
Neanderthals I have to deal with.

50
00:05:00,680 --> 00:05:01,761
Oh, you haven't changed.

51
00:05:01,840 --> 00:05:03,922
You're still a perfectionist,
a snob, a genius,

52
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:05,968
with all the charm
of a typhus epidemic.

53
00:05:06,040 --> 00:05:09,203
Well, can I help it if I'm
surrounded by assassins?

54
00:05:09,280 --> 00:05:12,250
Nonetheless,
you held us spellbound.

55
00:05:12,320 --> 00:05:15,210
And that last effect, from the
sarcophagus into the empty chair,

56
00:05:15,280 --> 00:05:16,805
when you swivel around...

57
00:05:16,920 --> 00:05:20,163
I mean, I do a vanish-and-reappearance
trick in my show

58
00:05:20,240 --> 00:05:21,810
where I transport
my pretty assistant

59
00:05:21,880 --> 00:05:23,450
From one side of the stage
to the other

60
00:05:23,520 --> 00:05:24,520
in a steamer trunk,

61
00:05:24,560 --> 00:05:26,847
but it is nothing
compared to what you do.

62
00:05:27,520 --> 00:05:29,568
I invented
that effect myself.

63
00:05:29,680 --> 00:05:30,966
And if you're very good,

64
00:05:31,040 --> 00:05:32,724
when we have more time,
I'll teach you all the moves.

65
00:05:32,800 --> 00:05:35,770
It's actually... It's very simple.
You can do it anywhere.

66
00:05:35,840 --> 00:05:37,365
It's a spectacular trick.

67
00:05:37,480 --> 00:05:39,687
It's so good to see you.
How long has it been?

68
00:05:39,760 --> 00:05:42,411
It's a year, at least.
And the tour's going well?

69
00:05:42,480 --> 00:05:45,165
Yes, it's going quite well.
It concludes this week.

70
00:05:45,280 --> 00:05:48,011
Munich was good.
Barcelona adored me.

71
00:05:48,080 --> 00:05:50,686
And you'll never guess who came
to see the show in Zurich.

72
00:05:50,760 --> 00:05:52,967
Enid Paxton.
Enid Paxton?

73
00:05:53,080 --> 00:05:54,241
Little thing
in third form,

74
00:05:54,320 --> 00:05:55,731
we both used her
as an assistant

75
00:05:55,800 --> 00:05:57,450
when we decided to become magicians.
Ah...

76
00:05:57,520 --> 00:05:59,363
You sawed her in half,
and I cut her head off.

77
00:05:59,440 --> 00:06:01,329
Well, she was
a game girl.

78
00:06:01,400 --> 00:06:03,209
Uh, how is she?
Oh, she's fine.

79
00:06:03,280 --> 00:06:05,123
You don't really notice
any of the scars.

80
00:06:05,200 --> 00:06:06,804
Of course, she's fatter
than my elephant.

81
00:06:06,880 --> 00:06:09,121
What? Pretty little Enid
with the curls?

82
00:06:09,200 --> 00:06:10,929
Well, the years
can be cruel, Howard.

83
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:14,800
"Life is nasty, brutish and
short," as the man said.

84
00:06:14,880 --> 00:06:16,769
Was it Hobbes? Yes, I
believe it was Hobbes.

85
00:06:16,840 --> 00:06:18,171
I'd have got on
rather well with Hobbes.

86
00:06:18,240 --> 00:06:19,526
Shall we go
for a drink?

87
00:06:19,600 --> 00:06:21,568
Brilliant notion, Burkan.
We can catch up.

88
00:06:21,640 --> 00:06:24,803
Stanley,
I need your help.

89
00:06:24,880 --> 00:06:28,327
Ah, the plot thickens.
I'll buy you a scotch.

90
00:06:28,400 --> 00:06:30,721
(SINGING IN GERMAN)

91
00:06:50,840 --> 00:06:52,888
(SONG ENDS)

92
00:06:53,160 --> 00:06:55,481
(APPLAUSE)

93
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:00,288
The Catledge family
are wonderful people.

94
00:07:00,360 --> 00:07:02,408
Caroline Catledge is
an old friend of mine.

95
00:07:02,480 --> 00:07:04,448
They're a wealthy
Pittsburgh family.

96
00:07:04,520 --> 00:07:06,682
Father made millions
in coal before he died.

97
00:07:06,760 --> 00:07:10,845
They're socialites with several
houses, one in the south of France.

98
00:07:10,920 --> 00:07:14,925
Now, the thing is, there's a
young woman staying with them,

99
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:18,447
who has them believing
that she's a spirit medium.

100
00:07:18,520 --> 00:07:20,443
Oh, Lord,
not another fake psychic.

101
00:07:20,520 --> 00:07:22,409
What a pestilence
they are.

102
00:07:22,480 --> 00:07:24,926
They're taken with her
predictions of the future.

103
00:07:25,040 --> 00:07:27,486
Telling them what they want to hear.
Precisely.

104
00:07:27,560 --> 00:07:30,723
Hmm, and charging them for all
the good news she brings.

105
00:07:30,800 --> 00:07:33,121
Exactly right. And, of course,
she's a pretty young thing.

106
00:07:33,200 --> 00:07:35,726
Well, of course. A pretty face
never hurt a cheap swindler.

107
00:07:35,800 --> 00:07:38,804
Brice Catledge,
Caroline's brother,

108
00:07:38,880 --> 00:07:41,121
the heir
to the family fortune,

109
00:07:41,200 --> 00:07:43,601
fancies himself
in love with her.

110
00:07:43,680 --> 00:07:46,570
You know, I don't know
who I loathe more,

111
00:07:46,640 --> 00:07:49,211
those who use simple tricks
to prey on the gullible,

112
00:07:49,320 --> 00:07:52,449
or the gullible, who are so stupid,
they deserve what they get.

113
00:07:52,520 --> 00:07:54,648
Brice Catledge's
sister Caroline

114
00:07:54,720 --> 00:07:56,722
is married to a doctor,
a psychoanalyst,

115
00:07:56,800 --> 00:07:59,690
and he insisted on this
woman doing her séances,

116
00:07:59,760 --> 00:08:02,366
in the presence of
two renowned scientists.

117
00:08:02,440 --> 00:08:03,441
Oh, rubbish.

118
00:08:03,520 --> 00:08:06,091
Doesn't he know that scientists
are among the easiest to fool?

119
00:08:06,160 --> 00:08:08,322
Well, this is the thing,
I'm embarrassed to say,

120
00:08:08,400 --> 00:08:12,121
that I watched this woman work
from every angle, time and again,

121
00:08:12,200 --> 00:08:14,851
and I couldn't
find anything amiss.

122
00:08:14,920 --> 00:08:17,002
I mean, I watched every
move, and Lord knows,

123
00:08:17,080 --> 00:08:20,323
I know pretty much every mind-reading
and seance trick there is,

124
00:08:20,400 --> 00:08:24,007
but I couldn't find a flaw or spot
a single suspicious move and...

125
00:08:24,080 --> 00:08:25,241
(SIGHS)

126
00:08:25,320 --> 00:08:27,482
I began to doubt
my own clear thinking.

127
00:08:27,560 --> 00:08:30,803
You know, I thought,
"Maybe, she's the real thing."

128
00:08:31,440 --> 00:08:35,411
There is no real thing,
Howard! It's all phony!

129
00:08:35,480 --> 00:08:38,404
From the séance table,
to the Vatican and beyond!

130
00:08:38,480 --> 00:08:39,970
I can't believe
you're saying this.

131
00:08:40,080 --> 00:08:41,764
I'm very worried
for the family.

132
00:08:41,840 --> 00:08:44,571
If you could come and
observe her in action?

133
00:08:44,640 --> 00:08:46,688
After all, you are
the greatest debunker

134
00:08:46,760 --> 00:08:48,728
of fake spiritualists
in the world.

135
00:08:48,840 --> 00:08:51,446
There's not a single one
who's got past you.

136
00:08:51,600 --> 00:08:53,523
Olivia and I were all set
to take a holiday,

137
00:08:53,600 --> 00:08:54,965
travel through
the Galapagos.

138
00:08:55,040 --> 00:08:56,280
But you hate holidays.

139
00:08:56,360 --> 00:08:59,489
You'll spend your whole time in
your room practicing card tricks,

140
00:08:59,600 --> 00:09:01,602
and you'll never
see the big turtles.

141
00:09:01,680 --> 00:09:04,684
And besides, you've always
loved the south of France,

142
00:09:04,760 --> 00:09:07,206
and you could visit
your Aunt Vanessa.

143
00:09:07,280 --> 00:09:11,410
But if this woman knows she's being
watched by the great Wei Ling Soo,

144
00:09:11,480 --> 00:09:13,926
she'll make some excuse
not to perform.

145
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:17,049
The usual headaches,
resistance in the room...

146
00:09:17,160 --> 00:09:18,366
She'll never know
you're Wei Ling Soo.

147
00:09:18,440 --> 00:09:20,966
No one knows who you are
under all that chinoiserie.

148
00:09:21,080 --> 00:09:23,048
You can pose
as anyone you like.

149
00:09:23,120 --> 00:09:27,409
Well, if she's fooled you,
she must be very good.

150
00:09:27,480 --> 00:09:29,642
But she won't fool me.

151
00:09:29,720 --> 00:09:32,405
I can't wait to see what
gimmickry she's employing,

152
00:09:32,480 --> 00:09:35,848
unmask it, and throw
it back in her face.

153
00:09:38,800 --> 00:09:40,450
OLIVIA:
Postponing our holiday?

154
00:09:40,520 --> 00:09:41,760
STANLEY: I can't resist.

155
00:09:41,840 --> 00:09:43,604
You're driven, Stanley.

156
00:09:43,680 --> 00:09:46,081
Don't get angry with me, Olivia.
It won't be for long.

157
00:09:46,160 --> 00:09:48,766
Oh, okay, go.

158
00:09:48,840 --> 00:09:50,888
You've always had
the measure of me, Olivia.

159
00:09:50,960 --> 00:09:53,122
Ever since our
very first dinner,

160
00:09:53,200 --> 00:09:55,601
when I made your ruby ring
disappear from your finger,

161
00:09:55,680 --> 00:09:58,604
and reappear in
your soft-boiled egg.

162
00:09:58,680 --> 00:10:01,160
(CHUCKLES) If you recall, I quickly
figured out how you did it.

163
00:10:01,200 --> 00:10:02,884
Yes, you were
very impressive.

164
00:10:02,960 --> 00:10:05,770
Oh, it was simply a matter
of logic and common sense.

165
00:10:05,840 --> 00:10:09,765
I mean, you palmed the ring and
distracted me by spilling the salt.

166
00:10:09,840 --> 00:10:12,684
I believe it was my clear thinking
that attracted you to me.

167
00:10:12,760 --> 00:10:14,808
Yes, your logic and
common sense equal mine,

168
00:10:14,880 --> 00:10:17,247
but you have the added
quality of being beautiful.

169
00:10:17,320 --> 00:10:19,322
Mmm, you've said it
several times, Stanley.

170
00:10:19,400 --> 00:10:21,368
We're a match
made in heaven.

171
00:10:21,520 --> 00:10:22,931
(♪♪♪)

172
00:10:50,560 --> 00:10:52,801
VANESSA: What a
serendipitous pleasure

173
00:10:52,920 --> 00:10:58,006
to be surprised by my favorite
nephew and Howard Burkan!

174
00:10:58,080 --> 00:10:59,286
Little Howard.

175
00:10:59,400 --> 00:11:02,483
Uh, "Burkan the Great," if you please.
Of course.

176
00:11:02,560 --> 00:11:05,643
Of all my nephews and nieces,
you're the only one, Stanley,

177
00:11:05,720 --> 00:11:07,688
who isn't boring to
the point of perfection.

178
00:11:07,760 --> 00:11:09,728
Oh, I couldn't
agree more.

179
00:11:09,800 --> 00:11:12,007
If only you had a slightly
milder disposition,

180
00:11:12,080 --> 00:11:13,684
you might
actually have friends.

181
00:11:13,760 --> 00:11:16,161
Oh, l am his friend.
Notice I use the singular.

182
00:11:16,240 --> 00:11:17,810
Yes, he means
he can tolerate me.

183
00:11:17,880 --> 00:11:19,803
You may be Burkan the
Great to your public,

184
00:11:19,880 --> 00:11:22,963
but to me, you'll always
be little Howard Burkan,

185
00:11:23,040 --> 00:11:26,840
who took my favorite scarf, cut it
in half with a pair of scissors,

186
00:11:26,920 --> 00:11:29,048
waved his magic wand
over it,

187
00:11:29,120 --> 00:11:31,122
and it didn't
come back together.

188
00:11:31,200 --> 00:11:32,690
I was just
learning the trick.

189
00:11:32,760 --> 00:11:34,205
No, she never got over that.

190
00:11:34,280 --> 00:11:36,681
And to what do I owe
this unannounced visit?

191
00:11:36,800 --> 00:11:39,690
I'm here to expose yet another
fraudulent spiritualist,

192
00:11:39,800 --> 00:11:42,201
and I thought I'd warn you
I'll be dropping by
for black pudding.

193
00:11:42,280 --> 00:11:46,001
Oh, yes, the Catledges are holding
séances up at their place.

194
00:11:46,080 --> 00:11:48,367
They've apparently
met some gifted medium.

195
00:11:48,440 --> 00:11:49,726
It's the talk of
the Côte d'Azur.

196
00:11:49,800 --> 00:11:51,962
She's a little American
called Sophie Baker,

197
00:11:52,040 --> 00:11:53,405
and apparently
she's very sharp,

198
00:11:53,480 --> 00:11:54,891
but Stanley will get
the measure of her.

199
00:11:54,960 --> 00:11:56,530
I can't wait.

200
00:11:56,600 --> 00:11:58,125
(♪♪♪)

201
00:12:09,320 --> 00:12:10,890
Welcome!
Welcome...

202
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:12,650
How lovely to see you.
Bienvenue.

203
00:12:12,760 --> 00:12:15,127
George, Caroline, Stanley.
How do you do?

204
00:12:15,200 --> 00:12:16,440
GEORGE: Oh, hello.
Stanley.

205
00:12:16,520 --> 00:12:17,567
(SIGHS)
A great pleasure.

206
00:12:17,640 --> 00:12:18,687
George.
Charmed.

207
00:12:18,800 --> 00:12:21,326
Of course, George and Caroline
are the reason I'm here.

208
00:12:21,400 --> 00:12:23,402
They're a great deal
less gullible

209
00:12:23,480 --> 00:12:24,925
Than Caroline's
mother and brother,

210
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:26,570
and had hoped
that I would be able

211
00:12:26,680 --> 00:12:28,364
to reveal
the medium as a fraud.

212
00:12:28,440 --> 00:12:29,726
When she fooled
Howard Burkan,

213
00:12:29,800 --> 00:12:31,131
we knew
we were in trouble.

214
00:12:31,160 --> 00:12:32,491
But then when he said he
was best friends (SIGHS)

215
00:12:32,560 --> 00:12:33,607
with Wei Ling Soo...

216
00:12:33,680 --> 00:12:36,251
We're great admirers. Who isn't?
(CHUCKLES)

217
00:12:36,320 --> 00:12:39,244
I don't know if Howard told
you, her name is Sophie Baker.

218
00:12:39,360 --> 00:12:40,600
Have you heard of her or...

219
00:12:40,680 --> 00:12:44,446
No, I have not, but these sleazy
fraudsters change identity every month.

220
00:12:44,520 --> 00:12:47,763
And I omitted to mention
she's here with her mother.

221
00:12:47,840 --> 00:12:49,683
Ah, now, that says a lot.
Yeah.

222
00:12:49,760 --> 00:12:52,127
I hope you kept your eyes on
her mother during the seance,

223
00:12:52,200 --> 00:12:53,964
or did she dim
the lights too low?

224
00:12:54,040 --> 00:12:55,280
Caroline,
you were next to her.

225
00:12:55,360 --> 00:12:58,523
She held my brother's hand, and
she actually made the table rise.

226
00:12:58,600 --> 00:13:00,523
Well, I looked for the
usual devices, of course.

227
00:13:00,600 --> 00:13:03,171
I thought maybe, wrist lifts,
but they weren't there.

228
00:13:03,240 --> 00:13:06,005
She's promised to try and
make contact with my father,

229
00:13:06,080 --> 00:13:07,206
who died a year ago.

230
00:13:07,280 --> 00:13:09,123
As I was saying,
your mother and your brother

231
00:13:09,200 --> 00:13:11,248
are the victims
of a dishonest ruse,

232
00:13:11,320 --> 00:13:13,004
as your good sense
tells you.

233
00:13:13,080 --> 00:13:15,480
There is, of course, no spirit
world, and even if there were,

234
00:13:15,520 --> 00:13:18,603
you can be sure that some little American
gypsy would not be the one blessed

235
00:13:18,720 --> 00:13:20,484
to unlock its secrets.
(BOTH CHUCKLE)

236
00:13:20,560 --> 00:13:22,767
Only a low-grade halfwit
would fall for any of this.

237
00:13:22,840 --> 00:13:26,242
But you're not implying that her
mother and brother are halfwits?

238
00:13:26,320 --> 00:13:27,765
Well, l haven't
met them yet.

239
00:13:27,840 --> 00:13:29,251
But I'm sure
they're like most people,

240
00:13:29,320 --> 00:13:31,448
desperate for a little hope
in a world that has none,

241
00:13:31,520 --> 00:13:32,965
and willing to
believe anything.

242
00:13:33,080 --> 00:13:34,923
Who shall we say
you are?

243
00:13:35,040 --> 00:13:38,408
Introduce me
as Stanley Taplinger.

244
00:13:38,480 --> 00:13:40,528
I'm an old friend
in the import-export business.

245
00:13:40,600 --> 00:13:42,648
Understood. Mr. Taplinger,
up to the house.

246
00:13:42,720 --> 00:13:45,007
Come on, Howard.
(MAN SINGING IN DISTANCE)

247
00:13:45,080 --> 00:13:46,969
STANLEY: What is that
dreadful noise?

248
00:13:47,040 --> 00:13:50,681
My brother. He practices
serenading Sophie.

249
00:13:50,760 --> 00:13:53,161
<i>♪ Both thine
eyes are cute, too</i>

250
00:13:53,240 --> 00:13:55,811
<i>♪ What they do to me</i>

251
00:13:57,200 --> 00:13:58,611
<i>♪ Hear me holler</i>

252
00:13:58,680 --> 00:14:01,047
<i>♪ I choose</i>
a <i>sweet lollapaloosa</i>

253
00:14:01,120 --> 00:14:03,805
♪ <i>In</i> thee

254
00:14:03,880 --> 00:14:07,521
<i>♪ Thou sweet,
thou grand... ♪</i>

255
00:14:07,600 --> 00:14:08,681
Howard.

256
00:14:08,760 --> 00:14:10,000
HOWARD: Brice,
good to see you again.

257
00:14:10,080 --> 00:14:12,560
Can I introduce you to my
friend Stanley Taplinger,

258
00:14:12,680 --> 00:14:13,880
who's going to be staying. Oh.

259
00:14:13,920 --> 00:14:16,127
Pleasure to meet you. How do you do, Mr.
Taplinger...

260
00:14:16,200 --> 00:14:17,247
Taplinger... Taplinger.
Taplinger.

261
00:14:17,320 --> 00:14:19,520
And, uh, how long will you be
staying with us, Mister...

262
00:14:19,560 --> 00:14:21,608
Oh, not very.
I have business elsewhere.

263
00:14:21,680 --> 00:14:23,284
Ah, have you told him
about Sophie?

264
00:14:23,360 --> 00:14:25,806
Ah, now, is this the girl
that can read minds and such?

265
00:14:25,920 --> 00:14:29,129
Well, she gets these sensory impressions.
And, what are they?

266
00:14:29,200 --> 00:14:32,602
It's hard to explain. She
gets these mental vibrations.

267
00:14:32,680 --> 00:14:34,921
Her head vibrates?

268
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:36,604
Drink?
Thank you.

269
00:14:36,680 --> 00:14:38,648
Have you got a whiskey, Brice?
I absolutely do.

270
00:14:39,480 --> 00:14:41,687
Now, Sophie looked
into my eyes

271
00:14:41,760 --> 00:14:44,366
and told me things about me
she could never have known.

272
00:14:44,440 --> 00:14:46,568
About old girlfriends
I'd had,

273
00:14:46,640 --> 00:14:48,005
and places
I've traveled to.

274
00:14:48,080 --> 00:14:49,650
Good heavens. You think
she can do it with me?

275
00:14:49,720 --> 00:14:51,802
Oh, of course. Of course.

276
00:14:51,880 --> 00:14:56,044
Whatever questions you have
about life, the hereafter...

277
00:14:56,120 --> 00:14:57,406
Here, cheers.

278
00:14:57,480 --> 00:14:59,608
Perhaps there's
a departed loved one

279
00:14:59,680 --> 00:15:01,091
you wish
to make contact with.

280
00:15:01,160 --> 00:15:02,321
Sophie sees all.

281
00:15:02,400 --> 00:15:04,164
She can predict the future.
In short, she's a visionary.

282
00:15:04,240 --> 00:15:06,561
And, I'm told she's very
pleasant to look at.

283
00:15:06,640 --> 00:15:08,483
She's a visionary and a vision.
(CHUCKLES)

284
00:15:08,560 --> 00:15:10,847
Mother's agreed
to subsidize a foundation

285
00:15:10,920 --> 00:15:13,241
for the serious scientific
study of her work.

286
00:15:13,320 --> 00:15:16,085
Well, after this buildup, I'm
champing at the bit to meet her.

287
00:15:16,160 --> 00:15:18,242
She's doing some psychic readings
over at the Lounsberrys' house,

288
00:15:18,320 --> 00:15:19,765
but she should be here
any minute.

289
00:15:19,840 --> 00:15:21,490
And the Lounsberrys, I take
it, are wealthy marks...

290
00:15:21,560 --> 00:15:23,085
Uh, wealthy friends
of yours

291
00:15:23,160 --> 00:15:24,889
that she was anxious
to meet?

292
00:15:24,960 --> 00:15:27,406
Yes. How did you know?

293
00:15:27,520 --> 00:15:29,329
Mental vibrations.

294
00:15:29,400 --> 00:15:32,324
Excuse me? Telephone call, Mr.
Catledge.

295
00:15:32,400 --> 00:15:34,641
Your business office
in Paris.

296
00:15:34,720 --> 00:15:36,529
Ah, excuse me.

297
00:15:37,400 --> 00:15:41,291
He doesn't make any business
decision at all now

298
00:15:41,360 --> 00:15:43,283
without consulting
Sophie first.

299
00:15:43,360 --> 00:15:44,771
Well, what can
I say, Howard?

300
00:15:44,880 --> 00:15:45,881
He's a moron.

301
00:15:45,960 --> 00:15:47,803
Incidentally, Stanley,

302
00:15:47,880 --> 00:15:51,407
I think, if you could bottle up your
sarcasm a little more skillfully,

303
00:15:51,480 --> 00:15:52,845
it might help us
on our mission.

304
00:15:52,920 --> 00:15:55,491
Howard, we all hope someone will
come along with superpowers,

305
00:15:55,600 --> 00:15:59,889
but the only superpower certain
to show up wears a black robe.

306
00:15:59,960 --> 00:16:01,485
Mmm.

307
00:16:01,560 --> 00:16:05,770
Speak of the devil and superpowers,
I think that's her now.

308
00:16:05,840 --> 00:16:07,968
Yeah, there she is.

309
00:16:08,040 --> 00:16:09,371
(♪♪♪)

310
00:16:20,560 --> 00:16:21,891
HOWARD: Mr. Talmudge.
Hello.

311
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:23,126
STANLEY: Taplinger.
Hello.

312
00:16:23,200 --> 00:16:24,486
HOWARD: Oh, I'm so sorry. Yes.

313
00:16:24,560 --> 00:16:26,642
You're every bit as lovely
as you've been described.

314
00:16:26,720 --> 00:16:28,245
Thank you.

315
00:16:30,320 --> 00:16:31,810
Wait.

316
00:16:36,400 --> 00:16:41,406
Don't say anything. I'm
getting a mental impression.

317
00:16:42,120 --> 00:16:44,885
Are you from the Orient?

318
00:16:44,960 --> 00:16:46,325
The Far East?

319
00:16:46,480 --> 00:16:48,369
China?

320
00:16:48,440 --> 00:16:52,286
Have you been there,
or do you visit?

321
00:16:52,360 --> 00:16:54,362
Why do you say China?

322
00:16:54,920 --> 00:16:57,491
I just get that impression.

323
00:16:57,720 --> 00:17:00,451
And what impression
is that?

324
00:17:01,080 --> 00:17:02,127
No.

325
00:17:02,880 --> 00:17:03,881
(EXHALES) Huh.

326
00:17:04,840 --> 00:17:06,968
Never mind.
It's fading, it's fading.

327
00:17:07,280 --> 00:17:08,964
And you are her sister?

328
00:17:09,240 --> 00:17:10,446
Mother.

329
00:17:10,520 --> 00:17:11,681
STANLEY:
Mother, are you?

330
00:17:11,880 --> 00:17:16,363
What lovely cheek bones. The apple
does not fall far from the tree.

331
00:17:16,480 --> 00:17:18,448
And what do you do,
Mr. Taplinger?

332
00:17:18,640 --> 00:17:20,005
I'm...
Wait.

333
00:17:20,080 --> 00:17:22,890
Sophie, what impression
do you have

334
00:17:22,960 --> 00:17:25,725
of Mr. Taplinger's
line of work?

335
00:17:25,800 --> 00:17:27,290
I should say Sophie
has psychic gifts.

336
00:17:27,400 --> 00:17:29,562
STANLEY: Has she?
Hmm.

337
00:17:31,200 --> 00:17:34,727
It's not immediately clear,
although l...

338
00:17:34,800 --> 00:17:37,929
I do get some
vibrations suggesting

339
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:41,163
that Mr. Taplinger
travels a lot.

340
00:17:41,600 --> 00:17:43,090
Well, those are
excellent vibrations,

341
00:17:43,160 --> 00:17:44,889
but it's not an unreasonable
assumption, is it?

342
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:46,889
I mean, plenty of people
travel in their work.

343
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:51,483
I see Germany.
Have you been to Germany?

344
00:17:53,480 --> 00:17:56,450
Matter of fact, I did have some
business recently in Berlin.

345
00:17:56,520 --> 00:17:58,761
I'd say, that's
pretty damn impressive.

346
00:17:58,840 --> 00:18:02,322
Mr. Burkan, as you
may know, is a magician,

347
00:18:02,400 --> 00:18:05,882
who was brought here to observe
my daughter and find flaws,

348
00:18:05,960 --> 00:18:08,042
but has stayed
to marvel at her.

349
00:18:08,120 --> 00:18:10,043
Well, what have
I stumbled upon?

350
00:18:10,120 --> 00:18:12,088
You never told us what you did, Mr.
Taplinger.

351
00:18:12,160 --> 00:18:13,889
Neither did your daughter.

352
00:18:18,200 --> 00:18:23,684
For some reason, my mental
impressions are cloudy.

353
00:18:24,200 --> 00:18:27,568
Cloudy. When you say your
mental impressions are cloudy,

354
00:18:27,640 --> 00:18:30,723
are they cumulus clouds
or cirrus?

355
00:18:30,880 --> 00:18:33,451
Mr. Taplinger is a businessman.
MRS. BAKER: Ah.

356
00:18:33,520 --> 00:18:35,010
What line of business?

357
00:18:35,160 --> 00:18:36,844
The import-export trade.

358
00:18:37,360 --> 00:18:41,570
I see Chinese letters.

359
00:18:42,880 --> 00:18:44,325
Chinese writing.

360
00:18:44,720 --> 00:18:46,768
Perhaps, you're visualizing
my laundry ticket.

361
00:18:49,080 --> 00:18:50,445
You're making fun of me.

362
00:18:50,560 --> 00:18:52,289
I'm afraid you're in the
wrong part of the world.

363
00:18:52,400 --> 00:18:56,007
I import coffee beans
and cocoa from Brazil.

364
00:18:57,440 --> 00:19:00,410
Wow! Well, I didn't...
Really?

365
00:19:00,560 --> 00:19:02,528
MRS. BAKER: I think it's
time we moved along.

366
00:19:02,600 --> 00:19:04,523
Sophie's had
a strenuous afternoon.

367
00:19:04,600 --> 00:19:08,650
It is rather exhausting communicating
with the unseen world.

368
00:19:08,720 --> 00:19:12,327
Well, I'm sure Mr. Taplinger doesn't
believe in the unseen world.

369
00:19:12,400 --> 00:19:14,164
On the contrary, I always
thought the unseen world

370
00:19:14,240 --> 00:19:16,129
was a good place
to open a restaurant.

371
00:19:16,680 --> 00:19:18,523
Time to go, Sophie.

372
00:19:18,680 --> 00:19:20,569
The spirits have
to eat somewhere.

373
00:19:20,680 --> 00:19:24,241
Mr. Taplinger
is rather obnoxious.

374
00:19:24,320 --> 00:19:28,450
Obnoxious, but he's not
entirely unappealing.

375
00:19:28,760 --> 00:19:30,046
Congratulations, Stanley,

376
00:19:30,120 --> 00:19:33,761
you've managed to alienate the entire
household in a single afternoon.

377
00:19:33,840 --> 00:19:35,683
Oh, she's nothing
I haven't seen before.

378
00:19:35,760 --> 00:19:38,161
Pretty young thing with a stage
mother who handles the promotion,

379
00:19:38,280 --> 00:19:40,931
and who knows what else when the
lights are out at the seance.

380
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:43,571
I want you
to see her working.

381
00:19:43,640 --> 00:19:46,530
More importantly, I want to be
there when you expose them.

382
00:19:46,600 --> 00:19:48,320
Well, I mean, she's not
even a good actress.

383
00:19:48,360 --> 00:19:52,922
"I... I get the impression
of the Orient. China."

384
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:54,570
What utter bilge.

385
00:19:54,640 --> 00:19:56,722
HOWARD: Well, I thought
that was quite good,

386
00:19:56,840 --> 00:19:58,683
considering you
are Wei Ling Soo

387
00:19:58,800 --> 00:20:00,529
and you have just
been to Germany.

388
00:20:00,600 --> 00:20:02,364
Yes, it's all
very tantalizing.

389
00:20:02,440 --> 00:20:04,249
Oh, careful,
she's tricky.

390
00:20:04,320 --> 00:20:06,926
And yet,
she's a fraud, Howard.

391
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:08,570
Because there is
no sixth sense.

392
00:20:08,640 --> 00:20:10,642
There are five senses,
and no spirit world.

393
00:20:10,720 --> 00:20:12,563
But there are coincidences.

394
00:20:12,640 --> 00:20:14,210
Maybe she's made
some lucky guesses,

395
00:20:14,280 --> 00:20:17,648
but we have to be careful not to
build them into something more.

396
00:20:18,400 --> 00:20:21,563
Your daughter is going
to try to make contact

397
00:20:21,640 --> 00:20:24,689
with my dear
departed Harry tonight.

398
00:20:24,800 --> 00:20:26,723
Well, she's been waiting for
the right moment. Uh-huh.

399
00:20:26,800 --> 00:20:29,451
Sophie needs
the proper vibrations.

400
00:20:29,520 --> 00:20:34,560
Now, of course, we need to
purchase or build an establishment

401
00:20:34,680 --> 00:20:37,411
suitable for the operation of
our foundation. Of course.

402
00:20:37,480 --> 00:20:40,006
There will be various
assorted costs,

403
00:20:40,080 --> 00:20:43,402
and naturally, all the
students will pay a fee.

404
00:20:43,480 --> 00:20:47,087
And, I assume, profits will
go into psychic research?

405
00:20:47,200 --> 00:20:50,363
Oh, most of them, uh...

406
00:20:50,440 --> 00:20:54,445
Minus operating
expenses and sundries.

407
00:20:54,520 --> 00:20:57,490
You can count
on my support.

408
00:20:58,000 --> 00:20:59,764
I've always known
there had to be

409
00:20:59,840 --> 00:21:01,842
more to this life
than meets the eye.

410
00:21:01,920 --> 00:21:05,686
How could it be that what we see
is all there is to everything?

411
00:21:05,760 --> 00:21:08,491
And, that's such
a bleak thought.

412
00:21:08,560 --> 00:21:12,201
Why would God
go to so much trouble

413
00:21:12,280 --> 00:21:14,248
if everything
comes to nothing?

414
00:21:14,400 --> 00:21:15,447
Hmm.

415
00:21:15,520 --> 00:21:17,761
Well, Sophie is...

416
00:21:17,880 --> 00:21:23,011
Sophie is living proof that the
world is alive with hidden things.

417
00:21:23,080 --> 00:21:26,562
She's such
an uplifting creature.

418
00:21:26,680 --> 00:21:30,526
No wonder my son, Brice,
is so smitten with her.

419
00:21:31,200 --> 00:21:34,522
<i>♪ I'm always chasing</i>

420
00:21:34,600 --> 00:21:38,127
<i>♪ Rainbows</i>

421
00:21:38,440 --> 00:21:41,205
<i>♪ Watching clouds</i>

422
00:21:41,320 --> 00:21:44,642
<i>♪ Drifting by</i>

423
00:21:45,920 --> 00:21:48,161
<i>♪ My schemes</i>

424
00:21:48,240 --> 00:21:52,609
<i>♪ Are just like
all my dreams</i>

425
00:21:53,160 --> 00:21:59,122
<i>♪ Ending in the sky</i>

426
00:22:00,640 --> 00:22:03,883
<i>♪ Some fellows look
and find the sunshine</i>

427
00:22:04,120 --> 00:22:07,442
<i>♪ I always look
and find the rain</i>

428
00:22:08,120 --> 00:22:11,283
<i>♪ Some fellows
make a killing sometime</i>

429
00:22:11,640 --> 00:22:14,610
<i>♪ I never even make a gain</i>

430
00:22:14,760 --> 00:22:16,683
<i>♪ Believe me</i>

431
00:22:16,840 --> 00:22:20,526
<i>♪ I'm always chasing</i>

432
00:22:20,600 --> 00:22:23,922
<i>♪ Rainbows</i>

433
00:22:24,320 --> 00:22:28,848
<i>♪ Waiting to find</i>
a <i>little bluebird in vain ♪</i>

434
00:22:32,040 --> 00:22:33,804
You know that
I'm in love with you?

435
00:22:33,920 --> 00:22:36,491
You mustn't give your
heart away so quickly.

436
00:22:36,600 --> 00:22:39,046
You looked into my eyes,
and without even knowing me,

437
00:22:39,120 --> 00:22:41,088
you knew me better
than I know myself.

438
00:22:41,160 --> 00:22:43,970
You knew my dreams
and my ambitions.

439
00:22:44,040 --> 00:22:46,247
Please, don't tell me you're
in love with someone else.

440
00:22:46,320 --> 00:22:49,369
Oh, no, no, of course not.

441
00:22:49,440 --> 00:22:52,205
I never had time
to fall in love.

442
00:22:52,280 --> 00:22:56,365
Mother and I were always
traveling, you know?

443
00:22:56,440 --> 00:22:58,841
Unlike you, we're members
of the working class.

444
00:22:59,040 --> 00:23:00,530
That's over.

445
00:23:00,600 --> 00:23:04,127
I'm gonna take care of you and pamper
you for the rest of your life.

446
00:23:04,200 --> 00:23:05,884
Do you like to travel?

447
00:23:05,960 --> 00:23:07,724
I mean, on yachts?

448
00:23:07,800 --> 00:23:12,647
Do you like to go to parties and buy
jewels and clothes and go dancing?

449
00:23:12,800 --> 00:23:14,609
I'm a very good dancer.

450
00:23:14,680 --> 00:23:19,686
I'm sure I could get used
to yachts and jewels.

451
00:23:20,480 --> 00:23:23,802
GEORGE: I had an interesting chat with Mr.
Taplinger, as he's called.

452
00:23:23,920 --> 00:23:25,160
You did?

453
00:23:25,240 --> 00:23:29,564
Yeah, I'd say he has a classic
neurotic personality disorder.

454
00:23:29,640 --> 00:23:33,247
Yeah, brilliant parents
who didn't get along,

455
00:23:33,320 --> 00:23:37,291
closer to his aunt than his
mother, obsessed with mortality,

456
00:23:37,360 --> 00:23:41,604
believes in nothing, finds
life to have no meaning.

457
00:23:41,680 --> 00:23:45,605
Just a perfect depressive, with
everything sublimated into his art,

458
00:23:45,680 --> 00:23:48,445
and he is quite an artist.

459
00:23:48,520 --> 00:23:50,921
Oh, he began as
an escape artist.

460
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:54,925
Interesting choice if anyone ever
wanted to escape from reality.

461
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:58,607
But, like Freud,
he will not permit himself

462
00:23:58,680 --> 00:24:01,251
to be seduced
by childish thoughts

463
00:24:01,320 --> 00:24:03,766
just because
they're more comforting.

464
00:24:03,840 --> 00:24:06,730
Very unhappy man.

465
00:24:07,680 --> 00:24:09,250
I like him.

466
00:24:09,960 --> 00:24:11,530
(♪♪♪)

467
00:24:19,400 --> 00:24:21,402
Ah, Miss Baker.
Hello.

468
00:24:21,520 --> 00:24:23,204
Rested, I presume?

469
00:24:23,280 --> 00:24:25,965
Uh, yes, I had a bath.
I had a little nap.

470
00:24:26,040 --> 00:24:28,520
And now,
you're refreshed.

471
00:24:28,600 --> 00:24:32,491
Well, no, not entirely.
I had an unpleasant dream.

472
00:24:32,560 --> 00:24:34,881
I've had my share.

473
00:24:34,960 --> 00:24:39,170
I dreamt I was being followed
by a sinister Chinese.

474
00:24:39,240 --> 00:24:41,447
You have the Far East
on the brain.

475
00:24:41,560 --> 00:24:44,040
What do you think it means?
I don't know.

476
00:24:45,560 --> 00:24:47,164
Good evening.

477
00:24:47,240 --> 00:24:49,402
I understand you're
holding a séance tonight.

478
00:24:49,560 --> 00:24:51,403
She's been waiting
for the right moment,

479
00:24:51,480 --> 00:24:54,882
and now, she says, "The
planets are in alignment."

480
00:24:55,000 --> 00:24:57,162
And what do they have to
be in alignment with?

481
00:24:57,240 --> 00:24:58,765
Your vertebrae?

482
00:24:58,920 --> 00:25:03,084
Can you do the séance if someone
in the room is a non-believer?

483
00:25:03,400 --> 00:25:06,324
And when you
contact the spirits,

484
00:25:06,440 --> 00:25:09,171
will we be able
to see the souls?

485
00:25:09,240 --> 00:25:11,527
And how are they
different from ghosts?

486
00:25:11,600 --> 00:25:12,761
Or are they ghosts?

487
00:25:12,920 --> 00:25:15,241
I should think souls
are quite different.

488
00:25:15,360 --> 00:25:17,408
Have you ever heard of ectoplasm?
Ectoplasm?

489
00:25:17,480 --> 00:25:19,926
Now, isn't that a milky
substance rather like yogurt?

490
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:22,048
Oh, you are a joker,
aren't you?

491
00:25:22,120 --> 00:25:23,724
So, you're saying it
might look like yogurt,

492
00:25:23,800 --> 00:25:26,406
but it will be Mrs.
Catledge's former husband.

493
00:25:27,080 --> 00:25:28,570
(BELL RINGING)
MRS. BAKER: Dinner.

494
00:25:28,640 --> 00:25:30,881
MRS. BAKER: Sophie, come to dinner.
Mmm.

495
00:25:30,960 --> 00:25:33,691
Isn't the light perfect,
Mother?

496
00:25:33,800 --> 00:25:37,361
Really, what exactly
happens at a séance?

497
00:25:37,440 --> 00:25:39,283
You know, I don't
believe you're so naive

498
00:25:39,360 --> 00:25:41,169
as you make out
about the occult.

499
00:25:41,240 --> 00:25:43,811
I will admit, my Uncle Charles
once attended a séance

500
00:25:43,880 --> 00:25:46,247
where the medium made a lot
of amazing things happen,

501
00:25:46,320 --> 00:25:48,561
and weeks later, she was
unmasked and sent to prison,

502
00:25:48,640 --> 00:25:51,723
for defrauding people out of
substantial sums of money.

503
00:25:51,800 --> 00:25:55,441
Charles. Uncle Charles.

504
00:25:57,040 --> 00:25:59,361
Death by water.

505
00:25:59,440 --> 00:26:01,488
What did you say?

506
00:26:02,960 --> 00:26:05,850
What? Oh, I was just...

507
00:26:06,640 --> 00:26:10,326
I was receiving some mental impressions.
Excuse me.

508
00:26:11,560 --> 00:26:15,963
Come, Stanley, let's go to...
You look stunned.

509
00:26:16,040 --> 00:26:18,930
I had an uncle who
drowned many years ago.

510
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:20,047
And when I mentioned him,

511
00:26:20,120 --> 00:26:22,043
she lapsed into
a kind of fugue state

512
00:26:22,120 --> 00:26:24,566
and muttered
"Death by water."

513
00:26:24,640 --> 00:26:27,246
Well, she knew
that my sister married

514
00:26:27,320 --> 00:26:30,688
on March the seventh
to a bank manager.

515
00:26:30,760 --> 00:26:33,001
There's absolutely no way
she could know that unless...

516
00:26:33,080 --> 00:26:35,401
Oh, not you, too,
Howard! No!

517
00:26:35,480 --> 00:26:39,201
I'll make short work of her
tonight during the séance.

518
00:26:41,840 --> 00:26:45,561
I would like us
now to join hands,

519
00:26:47,240 --> 00:26:50,403
as we summon

520
00:26:50,680 --> 00:26:53,081
the unseen world.

521
00:26:55,120 --> 00:26:59,728
Now, we're here tonight
to contact the soul

522
00:27:00,600 --> 00:27:05,322
of the departed husband
of Grace Catledge,

523
00:27:06,240 --> 00:27:10,245
father of Brice
and Caroline.

524
00:27:13,040 --> 00:27:17,045
Now, I will try to achieve

525
00:27:17,600 --> 00:27:20,046
a trance state.

526
00:27:27,720 --> 00:27:30,610
I'm falling deeper,

527
00:27:30,960 --> 00:27:33,645
and deeper,

528
00:27:35,160 --> 00:27:37,686
into a trance.

529
00:27:38,520 --> 00:27:42,286
Harry Catledge,
give me a sign.

530
00:27:45,200 --> 00:27:47,726
Give us a sign!

531
00:27:48,240 --> 00:27:49,287
(THUMP)

532
00:27:49,360 --> 00:27:50,930
(GASPING)

533
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:52,843
GRACE: Harry?

534
00:27:53,960 --> 00:27:56,406
Is that you, Harry?

535
00:27:57,960 --> 00:27:59,849
SOPHIE: Spirit?

536
00:28:00,040 --> 00:28:02,884
Signal us once for "Yes."

537
00:28:03,680 --> 00:28:06,968
Twice for "No."

538
00:28:07,080 --> 00:28:09,765
GRACE:
Harry, are you okay?

539
00:28:10,360 --> 00:28:12,761
Are you happy?

540
00:28:13,120 --> 00:28:14,121
(THUMPS ONCE)

541
00:28:14,200 --> 00:28:15,201
Ah!

542
00:28:15,280 --> 00:28:19,569
Spirit,
if you can hear me,

543
00:28:21,640 --> 00:28:24,211
give me a sign.

544
00:28:28,320 --> 00:28:29,651
(ALL GASPING)

545
00:28:31,720 --> 00:28:34,007
That's not possible.

546
00:28:37,200 --> 00:28:39,726
I mean, damn it, Stanley,
we've both done levitations.

547
00:28:39,800 --> 00:28:43,600
I once raised a real tiger,
but we both have our tricks.

548
00:28:43,680 --> 00:28:47,321
There was nothing supporting this
candle, no threads, no wires,

549
00:28:47,400 --> 00:28:50,609
it was floating
until I brought it down.

550
00:28:50,680 --> 00:28:51,886
Um...

551
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:55,766
(STAMMERING) I... I was just telling Mr.
Pepperidge here

552
00:28:55,840 --> 00:29:01,085
how marvelously you made that candle
float with no apparent support.

553
00:29:01,160 --> 00:29:03,766
"Apparent,"
I think, is the key word.

554
00:29:03,840 --> 00:29:08,482
Is it "Pepperidge," or
"Talmudge," or "Taplinger?"

555
00:29:08,600 --> 00:29:12,764
Anyway, it was a wonderful,
wonderful, super trick.

556
00:29:12,840 --> 00:29:17,687
I mean, I grabbed the candle and found
absolutely nothing supporting it.

557
00:29:17,760 --> 00:29:19,967
That's because
there's nothing to find.

558
00:29:20,200 --> 00:29:23,886
My daughter is not some
commercial music hall attraction.

559
00:29:23,960 --> 00:29:27,009
She doesn't do tricks.
She is an adept.

560
00:29:27,360 --> 00:29:29,761
I hope I didn't disappoint
you at your first séance.

561
00:29:29,920 --> 00:29:31,843
Oh, I found it
nothing short of perfection.

562
00:29:31,920 --> 00:29:33,285
Well done, madam.

563
00:29:33,360 --> 00:29:35,522
I can't even remember the last
time I've seen Mother so happy.

564
00:29:35,600 --> 00:29:36,681
Will you join us?

565
00:29:36,760 --> 00:29:38,410
We're all going to hear
some really hot music.

566
00:29:38,480 --> 00:29:39,561
Hot music?

567
00:29:39,640 --> 00:29:40,926
Come on, Sophie, come on.
Yeah, we...

568
00:29:41,000 --> 00:29:43,446
I thought you said "All this
mental work was exhausting?"

569
00:29:43,520 --> 00:29:46,285
Oh, it is,
but I love hot music.

570
00:29:46,360 --> 00:29:48,249
Mmm. Well, I hope you're
not plagued tonight

571
00:29:48,320 --> 00:29:51,324
by the dream of
the sinister Chinese.

572
00:29:51,400 --> 00:29:54,483
You know, I figured out
who you represented.

573
00:29:54,560 --> 00:29:56,483
Really?
Yes.

574
00:29:56,560 --> 00:29:58,528
When I was much younger,
years ago,

575
00:29:58,600 --> 00:30:01,570
I went and saw Wei Ling Soo.

576
00:30:01,640 --> 00:30:02,766
Have you heard of him?

577
00:30:02,840 --> 00:30:06,401
He's a Caucasian who disguised
himself as a Chinese,

578
00:30:06,480 --> 00:30:09,484
and he billed himself as
the Great Oriental Wizard.

579
00:30:09,560 --> 00:30:12,370
I see, and did you
enjoy his performance?

580
00:30:12,440 --> 00:30:15,125
I did, very much.
He was brilliant.

581
00:30:15,200 --> 00:30:18,283
He, um, he vanished
a live elephant.

582
00:30:18,360 --> 00:30:19,441
And it was just...

583
00:30:19,520 --> 00:30:22,330
I mean, it just was
completely shocking,

584
00:30:22,400 --> 00:30:24,641
but of course,
it was mechanical tricks

585
00:30:24,760 --> 00:30:26,285
that one could learn
with enough practice.

586
00:30:26,360 --> 00:30:28,601
I see.
And, your performance?

587
00:30:28,720 --> 00:30:30,160
Oh, I wouldn't call
it a performance.

588
00:30:30,200 --> 00:30:31,531
Well, call it
what you will.

589
00:30:31,640 --> 00:30:33,085
I mean,
it's a type of trickery,

590
00:30:33,160 --> 00:30:36,004
like card magic or
vanishing an elephant.

591
00:30:36,320 --> 00:30:39,290
And I say
you're Mr. Wei Ling Soo.

592
00:30:39,600 --> 00:30:43,605
And I say there is nothing you
can do that I cannot duplicate.

593
00:30:43,720 --> 00:30:47,167
Oh, I don't doubt it.
You're great.

594
00:30:47,280 --> 00:30:50,648
But just because you can
duplicate my miracles,

595
00:30:50,720 --> 00:30:54,520
in no way proves
that mine are not real.

596
00:30:54,600 --> 00:30:56,250
(♪♪♪)

597
00:31:06,640 --> 00:31:09,211
It was quite a display.

598
00:31:09,280 --> 00:31:11,248
(CHUCKLES) I must say,
she impresses me.

599
00:31:11,320 --> 00:31:13,800
CAROLINE: And you saw
no signs of trickery?

600
00:31:13,880 --> 00:31:15,166
Not yet.

601
00:31:15,360 --> 00:31:18,364
Well, let's face it, Stanley,
you came to unmask her,

602
00:31:18,480 --> 00:31:20,608
and she's unmasked you.

603
00:31:20,720 --> 00:31:24,520
On the one side, yes, she's pulling
off these bewildering feats,

604
00:31:24,600 --> 00:31:26,443
and on the other
remains the simple fact

605
00:31:26,520 --> 00:31:28,284
that what
she's claiming to do,

606
00:31:28,360 --> 00:31:32,251
while exquisitely executed,
is simply not possible.

607
00:31:32,320 --> 00:31:34,402
But who's to say
what's possible?

608
00:31:34,480 --> 00:31:37,404
I'm a physician, and new
facts come to light,

609
00:31:37,480 --> 00:31:39,642
new discoveries are
made all the time.

610
00:31:39,720 --> 00:31:42,530
Things we never
dreamed possible.

611
00:31:42,600 --> 00:31:44,364
To cure someone
of blindness

612
00:31:44,440 --> 00:31:46,124
by having her
lie on a couch

613
00:31:46,200 --> 00:31:47,565
and talk about
her childhood.

614
00:31:47,640 --> 00:31:49,051
(CHUCKLES) I mean,
who'd have thought?

615
00:31:49,120 --> 00:31:52,169
Yeah, but don't you see it challenges
our whole concept of reality?

616
00:31:52,240 --> 00:31:54,846
I mean, if there's
an unseen world,

617
00:31:54,960 --> 00:31:57,440
an afterlife,
souls to contact,

618
00:31:57,560 --> 00:31:59,289
mind reading,
foretelling the future...

619
00:31:59,360 --> 00:32:02,603
Yes, it changes everything we've
held to be scientifically accurate.

620
00:32:02,680 --> 00:32:03,680
CAROLINE: It's true.

621
00:32:03,720 --> 00:32:05,609
If what she claims
was possible,

622
00:32:05,680 --> 00:32:08,411
everything would
surely take on new meaning.

623
00:32:08,480 --> 00:32:11,484
And yes,
very hopeful meaning.

624
00:32:11,560 --> 00:32:14,006
To think, if there
were more to life...

625
00:32:14,080 --> 00:32:15,764
(SHOUTS)
More what?

626
00:32:15,840 --> 00:32:17,683
That life
doesn't end with death?

627
00:32:17,760 --> 00:32:19,489
That the universe
works by design?

628
00:32:19,560 --> 00:32:21,130
That God exists.

629
00:32:21,200 --> 00:32:24,602
All right,
let's not get carried away.

630
00:32:24,680 --> 00:32:26,842
The woman is a charlatan.

631
00:32:26,920 --> 00:32:29,446
Because, depressing as the
facts of existence are,

632
00:32:29,520 --> 00:32:31,887
they are the facts.

633
00:32:31,960 --> 00:32:33,883
There is no
metaphysical world.

634
00:32:33,960 --> 00:32:37,442
What you see out there
is what you get.

635
00:32:37,520 --> 00:32:41,366
I think Mr. Nietzsche has disposed of
the God matter rather convincingly.

636
00:32:41,840 --> 00:32:43,649
(♪♪♪)

637
00:32:48,120 --> 00:32:49,645
(♪♪♪)

638
00:33:49,320 --> 00:33:50,845
Good morning.
Mmm.

639
00:33:50,920 --> 00:33:52,524
May I?
Mmm-hmm.

640
00:33:52,600 --> 00:33:54,921
Did you sleep well,
Mr. Taplinger?

641
00:33:55,000 --> 00:33:58,163
Or should I just call you
by your Chinese name?

642
00:33:58,240 --> 00:34:00,846
You are a very clever
little humbug, Miss Baker.

643
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:03,047
(SIGHS)

644
00:34:03,120 --> 00:34:04,690
What are you
doing today?

645
00:34:04,960 --> 00:34:06,724
I'm going
bird-watching with Brice.

646
00:34:06,800 --> 00:34:08,006
Do you want to join us?

647
00:34:08,080 --> 00:34:09,730
I can't think of
a more inane activity,

648
00:34:09,800 --> 00:34:11,723
watching little
winged creatures

649
00:34:11,800 --> 00:34:13,962
acting out nature's
pointless busywork.

650
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:17,207
Why don't you
join me instead?

651
00:34:17,400 --> 00:34:18,731
Where?

652
00:34:18,800 --> 00:34:20,962
I'm driving to Provence
to visit my Aunt Vanessa.

653
00:34:21,120 --> 00:34:23,248
She's a remarkable woman.

654
00:34:23,320 --> 00:34:26,290
We could have lunch. Chat?

655
00:34:26,360 --> 00:34:28,488
Actually, get to know
one another better.

656
00:34:28,560 --> 00:34:33,851
You think you'll trick me into
showing you how I deceive people.

657
00:34:34,120 --> 00:34:35,326
Come on.

658
00:34:35,400 --> 00:34:36,925
I'm sure Brice Catledge
can live

659
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:40,163
without drooling all over
you for a few hours.

660
00:34:41,960 --> 00:34:43,803
(SIGHS)

661
00:34:44,120 --> 00:34:48,762
I think I'd like
to visit Provence.
I've never been there.

662
00:34:50,760 --> 00:34:52,683
(♪♪♪)

663
00:34:59,080 --> 00:35:00,844
Tell me, doesn't it ever
trouble your conscience

664
00:35:00,920 --> 00:35:04,003
to fool that poor,
empty-headed Mrs. Catledge

665
00:35:04,120 --> 00:35:07,522
into believing
she's communicating
with her departed spouse?

666
00:35:07,800 --> 00:35:09,723
I could just as
easily ask you,

667
00:35:09,800 --> 00:35:11,689
doesn't it ever bother you
to creep around,

668
00:35:11,760 --> 00:35:14,047
dashing people's
dreams and hopes?

669
00:35:14,120 --> 00:35:15,281
Not if their hopes
are false.

670
00:35:15,360 --> 00:35:16,771
Even if their hopes
are false,

671
00:35:16,840 --> 00:35:18,285
if it helps them
get through life?

672
00:35:18,360 --> 00:35:19,771
Then you admit
you're a fraud?

673
00:35:20,360 --> 00:35:24,365
I wonder if you get your
cynicism from your grandfather,

674
00:35:24,440 --> 00:35:28,490
the merchant seaman
with the missing finger.

675
00:35:31,120 --> 00:35:34,044
The missing toe.

676
00:35:38,080 --> 00:35:40,128
Why are you staring at me?

677
00:35:40,720 --> 00:35:42,404
Where are you from?

678
00:35:42,480 --> 00:35:44,244
Kalamazoo.

679
00:35:45,400 --> 00:35:48,165
It's in Michigan.

680
00:35:48,240 --> 00:35:49,890
And, you're from London.

681
00:35:51,640 --> 00:35:53,961
I see a white
house in Belgravia.

682
00:35:55,920 --> 00:35:58,924
<i>Fourteen... No, 16.</i>

683
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:01,287
Wilton Crescent.

684
00:36:02,840 --> 00:36:05,081
A piano.

685
00:36:05,160 --> 00:36:08,084
Yes, that's all correct
and rather amazing.

686
00:36:08,640 --> 00:36:10,165
But <i>I</i> don't buy it.

687
00:36:10,240 --> 00:36:11,765
'Cause I'm a rational man

688
00:36:11,840 --> 00:36:13,330
who believes in
a rational world.

689
00:36:13,440 --> 00:36:15,602
Any other way, lies madness.

690
00:36:16,920 --> 00:36:19,207
You'd be happier
if I was a fraud,

691
00:36:19,320 --> 00:36:21,482
because then,
your whole fixed worldview

692
00:36:21,560 --> 00:36:22,686
wouldn't be shaken up.

693
00:36:22,880 --> 00:36:24,644
No, it's quite the opposite.

694
00:36:24,720 --> 00:36:27,929
If you knew how much I don't
want you to be a fake...

695
00:36:28,120 --> 00:36:31,442
Oh, but think how embarrassing
it would be for you.

696
00:36:31,520 --> 00:36:36,321
Your whole life, you spent publicly
crusading against spiritualism,

697
00:36:36,400 --> 00:36:40,564
and then, you'd have to come out
with it and say that you were wrong.

698
00:36:40,760 --> 00:36:42,603
But I'm not wrong.

699
00:36:43,160 --> 00:36:45,401
Is that why Jenny
dropped you?

700
00:36:47,440 --> 00:36:50,046
How could you
know about Jenny?

701
00:36:50,240 --> 00:36:53,164
I see long, blonde hair.

702
00:36:54,320 --> 00:36:56,129
A wonderful laugh.

703
00:36:58,080 --> 00:37:00,686
Yes, she had
a lovely laugh.

704
00:37:01,680 --> 00:37:03,842
But who wants
a pessimistic bore

705
00:37:03,920 --> 00:37:08,448
who hides in his room all day
and practices card tricks?

706
00:37:11,040 --> 00:37:12,610
No, I'll tell you
who wants a man

707
00:37:12,680 --> 00:37:14,569
who locks himself in his
room and practices all day,

708
00:37:14,640 --> 00:37:15,926
who's a committed artist.

709
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:18,241
Olivia, my fiancée.

710
00:37:18,320 --> 00:37:19,560
Mmm!

711
00:37:20,320 --> 00:37:21,367
Yes.

712
00:37:22,200 --> 00:37:23,725
Olivia. Hmm.

713
00:37:25,720 --> 00:37:27,688
I see a match
made in heaven.

714
00:37:27,760 --> 00:37:28,886
(♪♪♪)

715
00:37:50,480 --> 00:37:53,211
How can you eat so much?
We just finished lunch.

716
00:37:53,280 --> 00:37:55,647
I told you
I like to eat a lot.

717
00:37:55,720 --> 00:37:58,007
George's psychoanalyst says
it's because I need love,

718
00:37:58,080 --> 00:38:00,401
but to me, I'm just hungry.

719
00:38:01,680 --> 00:38:03,682
Oh, I mean,
a lot of people need love,

720
00:38:03,800 --> 00:38:06,565
but they don't
eat their way to it.

721
00:38:06,680 --> 00:38:09,763
You want some?
No, thank you.

722
00:38:09,840 --> 00:38:11,888
This is so beautiful.

723
00:38:12,040 --> 00:38:13,724
It's transient.

724
00:38:15,560 --> 00:38:18,848
Oh, Stanley, how nice
of you to drop by.

725
00:38:18,920 --> 00:38:21,969
And you, I take it,
must be Olivia.

726
00:38:22,320 --> 00:38:24,800
Olivia? No, no.

727
00:38:24,880 --> 00:38:27,770
Olivia is a brunette.

728
00:38:27,840 --> 00:38:33,006
And she's a bit taller than
me, and she's in London,

729
00:38:33,120 --> 00:38:35,009
anxious to get
on with her trip,

730
00:38:35,080 --> 00:38:37,082
so, she can get to
work on her book.

731
00:38:37,160 --> 00:38:38,446
I'm Sophie.

732
00:38:38,520 --> 00:38:40,363
Oh, you must be
the American

733
00:38:40,440 --> 00:38:42,090
the Catledges
say is so amazing.

734
00:38:42,160 --> 00:38:45,323
Sophie fancies herself a
telepathic, among other things,

735
00:38:45,400 --> 00:38:47,767
so, be careful what you
think, Aunt Vanessa.

736
00:38:47,840 --> 00:38:50,081
We all know the evil
workings of your mind.

737
00:38:50,160 --> 00:38:52,322
Stanley doesn't
believe in spiritualists.

738
00:38:52,400 --> 00:38:54,482
He thinks
you're all scoundrels.

739
00:38:54,600 --> 00:38:56,360
If so, you're a very
pretty little scoundrel.

740
00:38:56,400 --> 00:38:58,482
If you see all
and know all,

741
00:38:58,560 --> 00:39:00,244
where's my aunt
just been?

