00:47:13,080 --> 00:47:15,845
My aunt used to
bring me here as a boy.

953
00:47:15,920 --> 00:47:17,365
The roof opens up.

954
00:47:17,480 --> 00:47:19,005
Oh, really?

955
00:47:19,080 --> 00:47:21,401
You can see the universe.

956
00:47:21,480 --> 00:47:22,845
It's menacing.

957
00:47:22,920 --> 00:47:24,331
Can you open it?

958
00:47:24,400 --> 00:47:26,641
I hardly think that's the
brightest idea at the moment.

959
00:47:26,720 --> 00:47:28,404
We just ran away from that.
It's still up there.

960
00:47:28,520 --> 00:47:30,204
Oh, right, right.

961
00:47:31,880 --> 00:47:34,611
Just have to wait it out.
Hmm.

962
00:47:38,400 --> 00:47:41,051
What was so menacing
about the universe?

963
00:47:41,120 --> 00:47:42,360
The size.

964
00:47:43,280 --> 00:47:45,886
Of course,
I was much smaller, then.

965
00:47:48,480 --> 00:47:50,881
Poor Howard's car.

966
00:47:51,000 --> 00:47:52,968
Are you a little warmer now?
Mmm-hmm.

967
00:47:56,280 --> 00:47:59,523
Tell me, with all your
powers of prognostication,

968
00:47:59,600 --> 00:48:01,648
could you have
ever predicted,

969
00:48:01,720 --> 00:48:03,563
when you first saw me
vanishing an elephant

970
00:48:03,640 --> 00:48:05,449
onstage in my
Chinese ensemble,

971
00:48:05,520 --> 00:48:07,602
that you and I
would one day

972
00:48:07,680 --> 00:48:10,524
end up in a deserted
celestial observatory

973
00:48:10,640 --> 00:48:13,450
in a rainstorm in
the south of France?

974
00:48:13,520 --> 00:48:15,204
It's highly ironic.

975
00:48:15,280 --> 00:48:17,169
It's morbid.

976
00:48:19,360 --> 00:48:22,091
I feel sleepy. I'm going
to have a little nap.

977
00:48:22,480 --> 00:48:23,481
(SIGHS)

978
00:48:23,800 --> 00:48:25,290
(♪♪♪)

979
00:48:41,960 --> 00:48:44,281
The rain stopped.

980
00:48:44,400 --> 00:48:48,200
SOPHIE: it stopped a while ago.
I didn't want to wake you.

981
00:48:48,320 --> 00:48:50,926
You looked too
peaceful sleeping.

982
00:48:51,000 --> 00:48:55,085
Yes, it's the first peaceful sleep
I've had in a very long time.

983
00:48:55,200 --> 00:48:57,487
Does this thing
open the roof?

984
00:48:57,560 --> 00:49:00,211
Yes, let me show you.

985
00:49:00,280 --> 00:49:01,930
I've never
forgotten this.

986
00:49:17,280 --> 00:49:19,282
You find that menacing?

987
00:49:20,840 --> 00:49:22,046
No.

988
00:49:27,840 --> 00:49:30,525
I'd say it was
pretty romantic.

989
00:49:36,720 --> 00:49:40,441
BRICE: <i>♪ Who stole
my heart away</i>

990
00:49:40,640 --> 00:49:44,486
<i>♪ Who makes me dream
all day</i>

991
00:49:44,640 --> 00:49:48,281
<i>♪ Dreams I know
can never come true</i>

992
00:49:48,720 --> 00:49:52,566
<i>♪ Seems as though
I'll never be blue</i>

993
00:49:52,880 --> 00:49:55,167
<i>♪ Who</i>

994
00:49:55,240 --> 00:49:57,720
<i>♪ Means my happiness</i>

995
00:49:57,800 --> 00:49:59,006
<i>♪ Who</i>

996
00:49:59,080 --> 00:50:02,084
<i>♪ Would I answer yes to</i>

997
00:50:03,720 --> 00:50:06,291
<i>♪ Well, you ought
to guess who</i>

998
00:50:06,360 --> 00:50:07,486
<i>♪ Who?</i>

999
00:50:07,560 --> 00:50:09,528
<i>♪ No one, but you ♪</i>

1000
00:50:10,960 --> 00:50:12,962
Penny for your thoughts.

1001
00:50:13,480 --> 00:50:14,766
Oh!

1002
00:50:15,880 --> 00:50:17,291
Nothing.
(CLEARS THROAT)

1003
00:50:17,600 --> 00:50:19,602
Well, you know
what my thoughts are?

1004
00:50:19,760 --> 00:50:21,728
I've already told you
I want to marry you.

1005
00:50:21,800 --> 00:50:24,770
That we'll get married at summer's
end at the Donaldsons' yacht.

1006
00:50:24,840 --> 00:50:26,569
It's enormous,
and it can accommodate

1007
00:50:26,640 --> 00:50:28,324
all the guests
we'd want to have.

1008
00:50:28,400 --> 00:50:29,447
And then
after the wedding,

1009
00:50:29,520 --> 00:50:31,488
we sail it,
with those who wish,

1010
00:50:31,560 --> 00:50:33,210
from Monaco to Greece,

1011
00:50:33,280 --> 00:50:35,123
and then we honeymoon
on the Greek Islands.

1012
00:50:35,200 --> 00:50:37,202
What do you think?

1013
00:50:39,480 --> 00:50:43,087
That's pretty swanky stuff
for a girl from Kalamazoo.

1014
00:50:43,160 --> 00:50:44,764
And then
we'll live in Europe.

1015
00:50:44,840 --> 00:50:47,002
You'll run your foundation.
You'll be world-famous.

1016
00:50:47,080 --> 00:50:48,366
I'll be so proud of you.

1017
00:50:48,800 --> 00:50:51,406
You know, my mom has been so
happy since you've been here.

1018
00:50:51,480 --> 00:50:55,326
Before you came, she was so
glum, and now she's all aglow.

1019
00:50:57,120 --> 00:51:00,602
<i>Pierre!</i> Bring <i>the</i> boxes
up to <i>mademoiselle's room.</i>

1020
00:51:00,680 --> 00:51:01,680
<i>Merci!</i>

1021
00:51:01,880 --> 00:51:02,961
What are those?

1022
00:51:03,080 --> 00:51:04,366
Well, you know
those dresses

1023
00:51:04,440 --> 00:51:06,488
you were fawning over when
we walked through town?

1024
00:51:06,560 --> 00:51:09,245
I got them for you.
All of them.

1025
00:51:09,320 --> 00:51:11,448
I told you I was
gonna pamper you.

1026
00:51:13,880 --> 00:51:15,120
<i>♪ Who? ♪</i>

1027
00:51:15,680 --> 00:51:19,571
GRACE: Shall I sell the beach
house on the Jersey Shore?

1028
00:51:19,680 --> 00:51:20,966
(THUMPS TWICE)

1029
00:51:21,040 --> 00:51:22,530
Then, I won't.

1030
00:51:22,640 --> 00:51:24,404
I really didn't want to.

1031
00:51:24,480 --> 00:51:26,369
It has such
sentimental meaning.

1032
00:51:26,440 --> 00:51:28,363
I'm so glad you
said that, Harry.

1033
00:51:28,480 --> 00:51:29,686
BRICE: Go on.

1034
00:51:30,080 --> 00:51:31,081
Um...

1035
00:51:31,240 --> 00:51:35,325
Harry, I hope this question
doesn't embarrass you,

1036
00:51:35,400 --> 00:51:39,769
but I have to ask it.

1037
00:51:39,840 --> 00:51:42,207
Were you always
faithful to me?

1038
00:51:42,640 --> 00:51:43,641
(THUMPS ONCE)

1039
00:51:44,480 --> 00:51:46,448
I knew it!

1040
00:51:46,520 --> 00:51:49,569
Certain so-called friends of
mine suggested otherwise,

1041
00:51:49,640 --> 00:51:53,167
that you had a long affair
with Sally Summers.

1042
00:51:53,880 --> 00:51:55,291
(THUMPS TWICE)

1043
00:51:55,880 --> 00:51:58,531
No, I really
didn't believe it.

1044
00:51:58,600 --> 00:52:01,331
But I'm ashamed to admit,
I did wonder.

1045
00:52:01,400 --> 00:52:03,448
Oh, Harry...

1046
00:52:03,520 --> 00:52:07,366
I'm so relieved to know
that I was the only one.

1047
00:52:07,840 --> 00:52:09,410
(STAMMERING)

1048
00:52:09,760 --> 00:52:13,082
I... I was the only one,
wasn't I?

1049
00:52:13,960 --> 00:52:15,200
(THUMPS ONCE)

1050
00:52:15,880 --> 00:52:17,325
Oh!

1051
00:52:17,640 --> 00:52:20,041
How wonderful
you make me feel.

1052
00:52:20,240 --> 00:52:21,241
(CHUCKLES)

1053
00:52:21,360 --> 00:52:23,806
SOPHIE: Well, look who's strolling
the grounds this morning!

1054
00:52:23,880 --> 00:52:25,166
Why aren't you in
your room, practicing?

1055
00:52:25,240 --> 00:52:27,242
I'm too excited
to lock myself away.

1056
00:52:27,320 --> 00:52:28,481
What are you
and Brice up to?

1057
00:52:28,560 --> 00:52:30,528
Brice is away for
the week, in Paris.

1058
00:52:30,600 --> 00:52:32,807
Mother and I are going swimming.
Ah!

1059
00:52:32,920 --> 00:52:35,002
I'm sure swimming isn't
your favorite pastime.

1060
00:52:35,080 --> 00:52:37,162
Nonsense.
I accept your invitation.

1061
00:52:37,240 --> 00:52:38,480
Just need to buy
a bathing suit,

1062
00:52:38,520 --> 00:52:39,601
and I'll, uh, meet you
by the pool.

1063
00:52:39,680 --> 00:52:40,966
We're not going
to the pool.

1064
00:52:41,080 --> 00:52:42,445
We prefer to
swim off the rocks.

1065
00:52:42,520 --> 00:52:44,329
The rocks? Even better.

1066
00:52:44,400 --> 00:52:46,971
Live dangerously, I say.
You only live once.

1067
00:52:47,040 --> 00:52:48,371
Or maybe two
or three times,

1068
00:52:48,440 --> 00:52:50,841
depending on your
supply of ectoplasm.

1069
00:52:51,560 --> 00:52:52,800
SOPHIE: You are a much
better swimmer

1070
00:52:52,880 --> 00:52:54,120
than I would
have imagined.

1071
00:52:54,200 --> 00:52:56,009
STANLEY: I'm also
a much better dancer.

1072
00:52:56,080 --> 00:52:58,811
Really? You must take
me dancing sometime.

1073
00:52:58,880 --> 00:53:00,166
Perhaps I shall,

1074
00:53:00,280 --> 00:53:04,285
now that life is no longer weary,
stale, flat and unprofitable.

1075
00:53:04,360 --> 00:53:06,124
Oh, that's from something.

1076
00:53:06,200 --> 00:53:08,202
Is that Dickens?

1077
00:53:08,280 --> 00:53:09,850
Oh, dear, poor thing.

1078
00:53:09,920 --> 00:53:13,049
Madam, your wunderkind has
much catching up to do. Huh?

1079
00:53:13,120 --> 00:53:14,326
Isn't that Dickens?

1080
00:53:14,400 --> 00:53:15,811
That's Dickens.

1081
00:53:15,920 --> 00:53:17,490
(♪♪♪)

1082
00:53:37,800 --> 00:53:39,564
STANLEY: The Seventh is
actually one of my favorites

1083
00:53:39,640 --> 00:53:40,766
of Beethoven's
symphonies,

1084
00:53:40,840 --> 00:53:42,046
but if you
haven't heard them,

1085
00:53:42,120 --> 00:53:44,407
the string
quartets are sublime.

1086
00:53:44,480 --> 00:53:47,962
Especially the late ones,
the 15th and the 16th.

1087
00:53:48,040 --> 00:53:50,691
Of course, they are rather
intellectually demanding,

1088
00:53:50,760 --> 00:53:51,841
but that's the thing
about intelligence.

1089
00:53:51,920 --> 00:53:53,445
You must never despair.

1090
00:53:53,520 --> 00:53:55,329
Yours can be raised.

1091
00:54:04,640 --> 00:54:05,926
You know,
it's extraordinary.

1092
00:54:06,000 --> 00:54:09,243
I have smelled these
flowers 100 times,

1093
00:54:09,320 --> 00:54:13,450
and yet I have never really
smelled them until now.

1094
00:54:13,560 --> 00:54:15,244
What a pity.

1095
00:54:15,320 --> 00:54:18,802
All the rest of the human
race that you consider boobs,

1096
00:54:18,880 --> 00:54:21,087
smelling flowers
and you all left out.

1097
00:54:21,160 --> 00:54:23,049
Now, wait. Yes.

1098
00:54:23,120 --> 00:54:26,249
They... They've enjoyed,
but mindlessly,

1099
00:54:26,320 --> 00:54:27,287
because they never thought.

1100
00:54:27,360 --> 00:54:29,601
They never...
They never stopped

1101
00:54:29,680 --> 00:54:33,321
for a moment to consider what a
rotten deal it all appears to be.

1102
00:54:33,400 --> 00:54:36,449
To be born,
to have committed no crime,

1103
00:54:36,520 --> 00:54:38,522
and yet to be
sentenced to death.

1104
00:54:39,040 --> 00:54:42,601
Ah, but notice I say,
"Appears to be."

1105
00:54:43,160 --> 00:54:46,721
Alvin, hello.
It's Stanley Crawford.

1106
00:54:46,800 --> 00:54:48,404
Yes, Wei Ling Crawford.

1107
00:54:48,480 --> 00:54:50,050
How are you?

1108
00:54:50,120 --> 00:54:51,360
Good, splendid.

1109
00:54:51,440 --> 00:54:55,001
Listen, Alvin, I have the story
of a lifetime for your paper

1110
00:54:55,080 --> 00:54:57,686
and I wanted you
to have it first.

1111
00:54:57,760 --> 00:55:00,240
No... Well, yes,
it is a...

1112
00:55:00,320 --> 00:55:02,129
It's a theatrical piece,
but it's...

1113
00:55:02,240 --> 00:55:04,083
It's much more
than that, much more.

1114
00:55:04,160 --> 00:55:05,924
It's science, it's...

1115
00:55:06,000 --> 00:55:09,129
It's philosophy,
it's religion.

1116
00:55:15,440 --> 00:55:17,727
Brice is coming home
tonight from Paris.

1117
00:55:17,800 --> 00:55:20,280
The week went so fast.

1118
00:55:20,360 --> 00:55:23,284
Have you decided to accept
Brice's marriage proposal?

1119
00:55:24,160 --> 00:55:25,160
Well...
(SIGHS)

1120
00:55:25,200 --> 00:55:27,089
He is pushing me
very hard.

1121
00:55:27,160 --> 00:55:29,322
Well, I'd grab it
if I were you.

1122
00:55:29,400 --> 00:55:30,481
I mean, it'd be logical.

1123
00:55:30,560 --> 00:55:31,641
An uneducated nobody

1124
00:55:31,720 --> 00:55:33,529
from some
ridiculous-sounding city,

1125
00:55:33,640 --> 00:55:37,850
gifted, miraculously, through
no achievement of your own,

1126
00:55:37,920 --> 00:55:40,810
and now you've developed
a taste for high living...

1127
00:55:40,880 --> 00:55:43,121
Yachts, motorcars.

1128
00:55:43,200 --> 00:55:45,168
You know, Stanley,

1129
00:55:45,240 --> 00:55:49,689
I'm not quite as desperate
as you make me out to be.

1130
00:55:50,920 --> 00:55:53,810
There have actually
been a number of,

1131
00:55:53,880 --> 00:55:56,690
I don't know, substantial men who
have fallen in love with me.

1132
00:55:56,760 --> 00:55:58,205
Really?
Mmm-hmm.

1133
00:55:58,280 --> 00:56:00,521
Hmm. Well, you could've
fooled me.

1134
00:56:00,600 --> 00:56:02,364
Although,
with the ability you have,

1135
00:56:02,440 --> 00:56:06,286
one does automatically
become intriguing...

1136
00:56:06,360 --> 00:56:08,044
And you do have
agreeable features,

1137
00:56:08,120 --> 00:56:10,964
but it's your gift,
I'm sure, which is...

1138
00:56:12,400 --> 00:56:15,882
Well, l wouldn't say charming,
but it is impressive.

1139
00:56:17,480 --> 00:56:20,802
I mean, even you just said
I have agreeable features.

1140
00:56:21,480 --> 00:56:22,970
They're more
than agreeable.

1141
00:56:23,040 --> 00:56:25,088
Provided the light
hits you just so.

1142
00:56:25,640 --> 00:56:28,769
Can I ask what time
of day that might be?

1143
00:56:28,840 --> 00:56:32,686
Just in case I ever need to look
my best for a job interview?

1144
00:56:32,760 --> 00:56:35,206
Dusk. You're
prettiest at about 8:20

1145
00:56:35,280 --> 00:56:37,408
in the summer,
when the light is fading.

1146
00:56:37,480 --> 00:56:39,721
Oh, I see,
the light must be fading,

1147
00:56:39,800 --> 00:56:41,802
so that
I'm not too visible.

1148
00:56:42,240 --> 00:56:45,130
Exactly. I'm thinking when I do
the vanishing elephant trick,

1149
00:56:45,200 --> 00:56:48,249
you must be lit precisely
as I light the elephant.

1150
00:56:48,480 --> 00:56:49,481
Oh!

1151
00:56:49,760 --> 00:56:51,649
I don't think
I'll pursue that.

1152
00:56:52,600 --> 00:56:54,762
You coming to the ball,
at the palace?

1153
00:56:55,240 --> 00:56:57,049
Of course I am.

1154
00:56:57,120 --> 00:56:59,646
My whole life I've wanted
to go to a ball like that.

1155
00:57:00,880 --> 00:57:02,086
Do you have a date?

1156
00:57:02,160 --> 00:57:03,764
I do, indeed.

1157
00:57:03,840 --> 00:57:06,844
I'm going with the most charming
woman in the south of France.

1158
00:57:06,920 --> 00:57:08,445
My Aunt Vanessa.

1159
00:57:09,520 --> 00:57:11,170
I like her.

1160
00:57:11,320 --> 00:57:12,924
I am going to dance
and drink

1161
00:57:13,000 --> 00:57:16,288
and enjoy all the things
you have brought to my life.

1162
00:57:16,360 --> 00:57:19,091
Maybe you and I can even
have a dance together.

1163
00:57:21,040 --> 00:57:22,451
(♪♪♪)

1164
00:58:39,840 --> 00:58:40,841
(♪♪♪)

1165
00:58:43,120 --> 00:58:45,600
Didn't you say that we might
have a dance together?

1166
00:58:45,680 --> 00:58:49,651
Ah, your mental vibrations told
you my feet are killing me.

1167
00:58:49,720 --> 00:58:50,881
Please, be my guest.

1168
00:58:50,960 --> 00:58:52,689
She so appreciates
your support.

1169
00:58:52,760 --> 00:58:54,603
Aunt Vanessa?

1170
00:59:07,480 --> 00:59:08,970
(CHUCKLES)

1171
00:59:22,320 --> 00:59:24,368
You know that you're the
only person tonight

1172
00:59:24,440 --> 00:59:26,886
who hasn't made a comment
on my appearance.

1173
00:59:28,200 --> 00:59:30,202
I'm overwhelmed, Sophie.

1174
00:59:30,280 --> 00:59:33,250
I never dreamed you could
look this beautiful.

1175
00:59:33,320 --> 00:59:34,606
That's more like it.

1176
00:59:36,040 --> 00:59:39,044
You must have moved mountains
to achieve this effect.

1177
00:59:39,120 --> 00:59:40,724
Thanks.

1178
00:59:41,840 --> 00:59:44,411
And this is all without the
added benefit of the lighting

1179
00:59:44,480 --> 00:59:46,289
that you give
your elephant.

1180
00:59:47,440 --> 00:59:49,761
You know, tomorrow I'm doing
that press conference about you.

1181
00:59:49,840 --> 00:59:50,841
Mmm-hmm.

1182
00:59:53,280 --> 00:59:55,851
Tell me, um, Stanley.

1183
00:59:58,680 --> 01:00:00,921
Apart from my gift,

1184
01:00:01,000 --> 01:00:04,004
which has changed
your life so...

1185
01:00:06,520 --> 01:00:09,364
Have you not,
in the...

1186
01:00:10,400 --> 01:00:13,165
In the time that
we've spent together,

1187
01:00:14,360 --> 01:00:17,250
had any other

1188
01:00:17,320 --> 01:00:19,891
thoughts about me?

1189
01:00:20,800 --> 01:00:21,881
Well, I've already
told you,

1190
01:00:21,960 --> 01:00:23,564
I'm in awe of you.

1191
01:00:23,720 --> 01:00:25,802
I don't mean
as a mystic.

1192
01:00:25,880 --> 01:00:27,723
I'm...

1193
01:00:27,800 --> 01:00:29,689
I mean as a woman.

1194
01:00:31,120 --> 01:00:33,202
As a woman?

1195
01:00:33,280 --> 01:00:34,645
What an odd question.

1196
01:00:34,720 --> 01:00:37,803
I've never technically
regarded you as a woman.

1197
01:00:37,880 --> 01:00:40,121
You were a charlatan
who turned the tables on me,

1198
01:00:40,240 --> 01:00:42,641
and now I feel both
humbled and proud.

1199
01:00:42,720 --> 01:00:44,563
You're proud of me?

1200
01:00:45,240 --> 01:00:47,004
You? No, I'm proud
of myself

1201
01:00:47,120 --> 01:00:48,963
for being big enough
to admit that I was wrong

1202
01:00:49,080 --> 01:00:51,048
and foolish
all these years.

1203
01:00:51,120 --> 01:00:54,442
I've been rather snobbish
and, uh, and rude.

1204
01:00:54,520 --> 01:00:56,841
Condescending about
other people's faith.

1205
01:00:57,680 --> 01:01:02,129
So you never thought
about me as a female?

1206
01:01:02,200 --> 01:01:04,328
Well, I was always certain
you were not of my sex,

1207
01:01:04,400 --> 01:01:06,084
if that's
what you're asking.

1208
01:01:06,160 --> 01:01:07,844
And quite good
to look at.

1209
01:01:07,920 --> 01:01:09,410
I mean, comparatively.

1210
01:01:09,480 --> 01:01:12,245
I've exposed some
pretty unattractive mediums,

1211
01:01:12,320 --> 01:01:14,243
a number of
horrible-looking creatures.

1212
01:01:14,320 --> 01:01:17,847
You do understand,
I'm seriously considering

1213
01:01:17,920 --> 01:01:20,048
marrying Brice Catledge?

1214
01:01:20,160 --> 01:01:22,049
Well, I think
you'd be insane not to.

1215
01:01:22,640 --> 01:01:25,041
You don't see it as

1216
01:01:25,800 --> 01:01:28,406
a little hasty of me?

1217
01:01:28,480 --> 01:01:30,209
Well, it's you who can
foretell the future,

1218
01:01:30,280 --> 01:01:33,363
and I'm sure your vibrations
are very positive.

1219
01:01:33,440 --> 01:01:35,249
And common sense
would say that this man

1220
01:01:35,320 --> 01:01:36,606
is a tremendous catch
for you.

1221
01:01:36,720 --> 01:01:40,361
Far beyond what you could hope,
given your trivial resume.

1222
01:01:40,440 --> 01:01:42,568
And of course, now that
you're emerging as a...

1223
01:01:42,640 --> 01:01:45,041
As a phenomenon, you'll always
be able to do quite well,

1224
01:01:45,120 --> 01:01:48,522
financially, although nothing
like the Catledge fortune.

1225
01:01:48,640 --> 01:01:50,802
And most of your time
will be spent with your...

1226
01:01:50,880 --> 01:01:53,690
Your foundation,
where he'll be a great help.

1227
01:01:54,280 --> 01:01:56,851
So the time that
we've spent together,

1228
01:01:56,920 --> 01:01:59,048
has just had

1229
01:01:59,120 --> 01:02:01,964
no impact on you

1230
01:02:02,040 --> 01:02:03,485
whatsoever?

1231
01:02:06,120 --> 01:02:08,168
I say, don't...

1232
01:02:08,800 --> 01:02:12,771
You don't tell me you're experiencing
romantic feelings for me?

1233
01:02:13,480 --> 01:02:15,369
What if I was?

1234
01:02:15,440 --> 01:02:16,726
Well, that's absurd.

1235
01:02:16,800 --> 01:02:20,088
(STAMMERING) You imagined
that you and I...

1236
01:02:22,720 --> 01:02:25,963
Isn't it enough you've opened
my eyes to the joy of living?

1237
01:02:26,040 --> 01:02:27,371
I mean,
you've conquered my mind.

1238
01:02:27,440 --> 01:02:30,011
Do you, do you also need
to conquer my heart?

1239
01:02:30,080 --> 01:02:33,004
I just thought, in the time
that we had spent together

1240
01:02:34,360 --> 01:02:35,691
<i>that you...</i>

1241
01:02:35,760 --> 01:02:37,569
Don't misunderstand me.

1242
01:02:37,680 --> 01:02:39,603
I hold you in the highest
possible esteem,

1243
01:02:39,680 --> 01:02:42,081
and tomorrow, I am prepared
to tell the world as much.

1244
01:02:42,680 --> 01:02:43,841
Excuse me.

1245
01:02:50,160 --> 01:02:52,481
VANESSA:
Ah, there you are, Stanley.

1246
01:02:52,560 --> 01:02:56,770
I don't know about you,
but I danced till dawn.

1247
01:02:56,840 --> 01:02:58,604
Can you believe the little
medium has grown fond of me?

1248
01:02:58,680 --> 01:03:00,808
Well, why shouldn't she?
According to the newspapers,

1249
01:03:00,920 --> 01:03:02,251
you're her
greatest press agent.

1250
01:03:02,320 --> 01:03:04,800
No, no, I mean... I mean, she's
emotionally taken with me.

1251
01:03:04,880 --> 01:03:07,201
I believe she fancies herself
falling in love with me.

1252
01:03:07,280 --> 01:03:08,520
But you're both
spoken for.

1253
01:03:08,680 --> 01:03:10,444
I know.
It defies all reason.

1254
01:03:10,520 --> 01:03:13,330
She's on the verge of
capturing a rich young man,

1255
01:03:13,400 --> 01:03:14,890
dullard that he is.

1256
01:03:14,960 --> 01:03:17,486
And Olivia and I are,
by her own vibrations,

1257
01:03:17,560 --> 01:03:19,130
the acme of congruity.

1258
01:03:19,200 --> 01:03:22,204
Well, it seems you've given
the matter some thought.

1259
01:03:22,280 --> 01:03:24,123
I was rather taken aback.

1260
01:03:24,200 --> 01:03:26,806
She is looking rather
stunning this evening.

1261
01:03:26,880 --> 01:03:28,405
Yes, to be sure.

1262
01:03:29,560 --> 01:03:31,289
She did make a rather

1263
01:03:31,400 --> 01:03:33,448
surprising entrance.

1264
01:03:33,520 --> 01:03:36,763
Come, I've got to
drive back to Provence,

1265
01:03:36,840 --> 01:03:40,162
and you have some journalists
to see in a few hours.

1266
01:03:40,240 --> 01:03:41,241
(CHUCKLES)

1267
01:03:42,240 --> 01:03:43,730
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

1268
01:03:43,840 --> 01:03:46,411
How did you first
discover Miss Baker?

1269
01:03:46,840 --> 01:03:50,401
I came to unmask her, as I
have done countless others,

1270
01:03:50,480 --> 01:03:52,050
but after trying
every which way,

1271
01:03:52,120 --> 01:03:55,442
came to the indisputable
conclusion

1272
01:03:55,560 --> 01:03:57,688
that she is
a genuine medium.

1273
01:03:57,760 --> 01:04:01,003
How can you be so certain
she's authentic?

1274
01:04:01,160 --> 01:04:03,162
I know all the tricks.

1275
01:04:03,240 --> 01:04:04,810
Conjuring is
my life's passion.

1276
01:04:04,880 --> 01:04:07,611
Debunking fake mediums,
my specialty.

1277
01:04:07,760 --> 01:04:09,762
What are her
plans for the future?

1278
01:04:09,840 --> 01:04:11,649
She plans to
start a foundation

1279
01:04:11,760 --> 01:04:13,603
and a school for
teaching the occult.

1280
01:04:13,960 --> 01:04:15,724
How does it feel
to be wrong

1281
01:04:15,800 --> 01:04:18,804
all these years
about the occult?

1282
01:04:18,920 --> 01:04:21,571
Well, on the one side,
I'm embarrassed,

1283
01:04:21,640 --> 01:04:24,371
but also thrilled to finally
be able to take a deep breath

1284
01:04:24,440 --> 01:04:26,363
and see new
possibilities in life.

1285
01:04:26,440 --> 01:04:28,408
So, it is fair
to say that you feel

1286
01:04:28,480 --> 01:04:31,563
the world is not as
rational and predictable

1287
01:04:31,680 --> 01:04:33,648
as you've always
so adamantly,

1288
01:04:33,720 --> 01:04:36,485
and sometimes insultingly,
claimed?

1289
01:04:36,880 --> 01:04:39,042
I deserve your criticism,
I know.

1290
01:04:39,120 --> 01:04:42,567
I've always been a rational man
with a great faith in science.

1291
01:04:42,640 --> 01:04:44,802
What can I say?

1292
01:04:44,880 --> 01:04:47,884
But it would appear
that perhaps,

1293
01:04:47,960 --> 01:04:51,885
to say I believe
in the dignity of man

1294
01:04:51,960 --> 01:04:53,724
is simply not enough.

1295
01:04:55,880 --> 01:04:57,530
MRS. BAKER: Even as a
baby, it was clear

1296
01:04:57,600 --> 01:04:59,887
from the very beginning
that she was a special child.

1297
01:05:00,000 --> 01:05:01,729
BRICE: It's gonna be
a world-class foundation.

1298
01:05:01,800 --> 01:05:03,802
MRS. BAKER: Yes, there'll be
students from all over the world.

1299
01:05:03,920 --> 01:05:05,251
You have to see her.

1300
01:05:05,320 --> 01:05:06,560
They are very
close friends of mine.

1301
01:05:06,640 --> 01:05:07,880
I came at once,
but she stumped me,

1302
01:05:07,960 --> 01:05:10,088
so l brought in Mr. Wei
Ling Soo under an alias

1303
01:05:10,160 --> 01:05:11,571
to unmask her.

1304
01:05:11,640 --> 01:05:13,404
Now you see the result.

1305
01:05:13,480 --> 01:05:15,050
And damned if
he isn't her biggest fan.

1306
01:05:15,120 --> 01:05:16,400
GEORGE: There you are.
Excuse me.

1307
01:05:16,440 --> 01:05:19,046
I have some seriously
distressing news. What?

1308
01:05:19,120 --> 01:05:20,770
Your aunt's been in a serious
automobile accident.

1309
01:05:20,840 --> 01:05:22,251
What happened?
Is she all right?

1310
01:05:22,320 --> 01:05:23,810
She's in critical condition
at the hospital.

1311
01:05:23,840 --> 01:05:26,241
I need to get there. Yes,
of course, I'll drive you.

1312
01:05:26,320 --> 01:05:28,687
Do you want me to come with you?
I know the way...

1313
01:05:46,240 --> 01:05:47,571
GEORGE: Jacques.

1314
01:05:47,640 --> 01:05:49,165
<i>Bonjour, George.</i>

1315
01:05:49,240 --> 01:05:50,446
This is Stanley.

1316
01:05:50,520 --> 01:05:51,681
Yes, how do you do?

1317
01:05:51,800 --> 01:05:54,007
So, how's she doing?
What's happening?

1318
01:05:54,080 --> 01:05:55,570
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

1319
01:05:55,680 --> 01:05:56,727
What was...

1320
01:05:56,800 --> 01:05:57,801
<i>En anglais.</i>

1321
01:05:57,880 --> 01:06:00,201
Oh, she's in
the operating room now.

1322
01:06:00,280 --> 01:06:01,566
Everyone is
doing his best.

1323
01:06:01,640 --> 01:06:02,641
So what do you think?

1324
01:06:02,720 --> 01:06:04,210
Is she going to be
all right?

1325
01:06:04,280 --> 01:06:06,965
At this moment,
it's touch-and-go.

1326
01:06:07,040 --> 01:06:08,610
Touch-and-go?

1327
01:06:08,680 --> 01:06:10,330
You... You can wait
there, if you want.

1328
01:06:10,400 --> 01:06:12,004
Touch-and-go.
You're in surgery with her?

1329
01:06:12,080 --> 01:06:13,650
Yeah, I know.

1330
01:06:19,840 --> 01:06:20,841
GEORGE: Now, don't worry.

1331
01:06:20,920 --> 01:06:22,160
They have
an excellent staff here.

1332
01:06:22,240 --> 01:06:23,810
You know, she's an
incredible woman.

1333
01:06:23,880 --> 01:06:25,689
She practically
raised me.

1334
01:06:25,760 --> 01:06:27,808
She's been through
a lot in her life.

1335
01:06:27,920 --> 01:06:29,604
Sit down. Let me
get you some tea.

1336
01:06:29,680 --> 01:06:31,842
No, I'm too
shaken up for tea.

1337
01:06:31,920 --> 01:06:33,604
Well, perhaps I can
scare up a whiskey?

1338
01:06:33,680 --> 01:06:35,170
Better idea.

1339
01:06:35,240 --> 01:06:36,844
You know, she shouldn't be
allowed to drive at her age.

1340
01:06:36,920 --> 01:06:39,287
Well, it's in the hands
of the doctors now.

1341
01:06:39,360 --> 01:06:41,328
I know how helpless
one feels,

1342
01:06:41,400 --> 01:06:44,961
but all you can do is
just keep calm and pray.

1343
01:06:45,040 --> 01:06:46,769
Yes.

1344
01:06:46,840 --> 01:06:49,002
The power of prayer.

1345
01:06:49,080 --> 01:06:50,161
Always ridiculed it.

1346
01:06:50,240 --> 01:06:51,924
Oh, as have I.

1347
01:06:52,000 --> 01:06:54,844
And yet,
some people swear by it.

1348
01:06:54,920 --> 01:06:57,605
You know, I know
this sounds crass,

1349
01:06:57,680 --> 01:06:58,920
particularly
coming from me,

1350
01:06:59,000 --> 01:07:01,731
a man of science, but...
(CLEARS THROAT)

1351
01:07:01,800 --> 01:07:03,450
If the worst happens,

1352
01:07:03,520 --> 01:07:05,045
at least through Sophie,

1353
01:07:05,120 --> 01:07:07,566
you'll be able to
contact her spirit.

1354
01:07:07,640 --> 01:07:08,687
(SIGHS)

1355
01:07:09,280 --> 01:07:10,691
Yes.

1356
01:07:11,520 --> 01:07:12,885
Yes, that's comforting,
isn't it?

1357
01:07:12,960 --> 01:07:14,121
Yes.
(LAUGHS)

1358
01:07:14,200 --> 01:07:16,441
I never thought
I'd say it, but yes.

1359
01:07:17,360 --> 01:07:18,691
Well, you buck up,

1360
01:07:18,760 --> 01:07:20,922
and I will find
that whiskey.

1361
01:07:51,320 --> 01:07:53,846
I don't know
if you can hear me

1362
01:07:56,160 --> 01:08:00,404
and I haven't always led
an exemplary life. I've...

1363
01:08:00,480 --> 01:08:03,484
I've not only
been a skeptic,

1364
01:08:03,600 --> 01:08:06,968
a non-believer,
but been much worse...

1365
01:08:07,040 --> 01:08:10,487
A man with contempt for,

1366
01:08:10,560 --> 01:08:14,610
for people who give themselves
over to the idea that,

1367
01:08:14,680 --> 01:08:18,446
that there's some kind of
benevolent father figure up there.

1368
01:08:20,480 --> 01:08:21,925
I've always said
it was childish,

1369
01:08:22,000 --> 01:08:23,923
wishful thinking,
strictly for primitives,

1370
01:08:24,000 --> 01:08:26,526
all these,
all these hopes about

1371
01:08:26,600 --> 01:08:27,840
a purpose for life,

1372
01:08:27,920 --> 01:08:30,571
a larger meaning.

1373
01:08:30,640 --> 01:08:34,804
That all our suffering
will somehow accrue to some

1374
01:08:34,920 --> 01:08:36,922
greater plan.

1375
01:08:40,280 --> 01:08:44,365
But if what I see
of late is real

1376
01:08:46,520 --> 01:08:48,966
then I don't have
all the answers.

1377
01:08:50,000 --> 01:08:52,651
It's possible,

1378
01:08:52,720 --> 01:08:54,643
even logical, that

1379
01:08:54,720 --> 01:08:57,644
we are here by design,

1380
01:08:57,720 --> 01:08:59,882
to serve
some higher ideal.

1381
01:09:01,960 --> 01:09:04,042
And that you

1382
01:09:04,160 --> 01:09:05,889
could be real.

1383
01:09:09,880 --> 01:09:14,488
And although I have no
right to expect anything,

1384
01:09:14,560 --> 01:09:16,961
my aunt,

1385
01:09:17,040 --> 01:09:18,485
whom I love,

1386
01:09:18,560 --> 01:09:20,562
is in mortal danger.

1387
01:09:22,760 --> 01:09:24,762
And so, I ask you...

1388
01:09:26,680 --> 01:09:28,682
l ask you...

1389
01:09:38,600 --> 01:09:40,329
Wait a minute.

1390
01:09:44,560 --> 01:09:46,847
This is the stupidest

1391
01:09:46,920 --> 01:09:50,129
load of twaddle
I have ever heard.

1392
01:09:51,800 --> 01:09:53,211
My common sense tells me,

1393
01:09:53,280 --> 01:09:57,808
I'm falling into
a seductive morass

1394
01:09:57,920 --> 01:09:59,604
of sugarcoated claptrap

1395
01:09:59,680 --> 01:10:01,808
because I want
my aunt to be all right.

1396
01:10:05,320 --> 01:10:07,971
That girl

1397
01:10:08,040 --> 01:10:10,008
is a fake.

1398
01:10:10,680 --> 01:10:11,886
(♪♪♪)

1399
01:10:13,320 --> 01:10:14,731
I told you the surgeons
were wonderful.

1400
01:10:14,800 --> 01:10:15,881
Should I not stay?

1401
01:10:15,960 --> 01:10:17,405
Well, there's nothing
for you to do here.

1402
01:10:17,480 --> 01:10:18,720
She's sleeping
comfortably.

1403
01:10:18,800 --> 01:10:20,325
She responded
well to the drugs.

1404
01:10:20,400 --> 01:10:21,640
The surgery
went beautifully.

1405
01:10:21,720 --> 01:10:22,926
She's out of danger.

1406
01:10:23,000 --> 01:10:25,731
You know, after you left,
I began to pray for her.

1407
01:10:25,800 --> 01:10:26,881
Really?

1408
01:10:26,960 --> 01:10:30,123
Then I rejected the entire
notion as pure poppycock.

1409
01:10:30,200 --> 01:10:32,487
And that includes
Miss Sophie Baker.

1410
01:10:32,560 --> 01:10:33,891
Is that right?

1411
01:10:34,000 --> 01:10:36,207
Well, if Sophie is a fraud,

1412
01:10:36,280 --> 01:10:39,648
then how does she do
what she does?

1413
01:10:39,720 --> 01:10:41,006
(♪♪♪)

1414
01:11:06,520 --> 01:11:07,726
on, Stanley! (GASPS)

1415
01:11:07,800 --> 01:11:09,086
Oh, we were all so worried.
BRICE: So worried!

1416
01:11:09,200 --> 01:11:12,443
You can imagine how anxious we
were about your Aunt Vanessa.

1417
01:11:12,520 --> 01:11:13,520
Yes!

1418
01:11:13,560 --> 01:11:14,766
Thank God!

1419
01:11:14,840 --> 01:11:16,444
Madam, I can assure you,

1420
01:11:16,520 --> 01:11:19,126
God had nothing
to do with it.

1421
01:11:19,200 --> 01:11:20,645
She had good doctors.

1422
01:11:20,960 --> 01:11:24,089
Yeah, we have all been
on tenterhooks, Stanley.

1423
01:11:24,160 --> 01:11:26,128
Well, couldn't Sophie
have predicted the outcome

1424
01:11:26,200 --> 01:11:28,168
and put all
your minds at ease?

1425
01:11:28,240 --> 01:11:30,049
Me? I didn't even know.

1426
01:11:30,120 --> 01:11:32,088
I was so mobbed
by all the press, I...

1427
01:11:32,160 --> 01:11:33,161
If I had known,

1428
01:11:33,240 --> 01:11:34,969
I would have gone
with you to the hospital.

1429
01:11:35,040 --> 01:11:36,201
Well, it's all over.

1430
01:11:36,280 --> 01:11:38,681
And, "All's well
that ends well."

1431
01:11:38,760 --> 01:11:40,410
That's not Dickens.

1432
01:11:41,240 --> 01:11:43,242
Well, now that
everything's ended well,

1433
01:11:43,360 --> 01:11:45,601
shall we repair
to the garden?

1434
01:11:45,680 --> 01:11:47,808
Brice? Mrs. Baker?
MRS. BAKER: Me? Great idea.

1435
01:11:47,880 --> 01:11:50,531
I'm so excited about the further
details of the foundation.

1436
01:11:50,600 --> 01:11:51,806
I want to talk over...

1437
01:11:51,880 --> 01:11:52,961
MRS. BAKER: Actually, there
are a few financial details...

1438
01:11:53,040 --> 01:11:54,565
Mother, I'm just
gonna stay here.

1439
01:11:54,680 --> 01:11:55,886
And thank you,
by the way.

1440
01:11:55,960 --> 01:11:58,440
GRACE: And I really want to
go into some detail

1441
01:11:58,520 --> 01:11:59,965
about how much...

1442
01:12:01,040 --> 01:12:04,522
Stanley, I can't imagine what has
been going through your mind.

1443
01:12:04,600 --> 01:12:06,967
I mean, Aunt Vanessa's
such a dear woman.

1444
01:12:07,040 --> 01:12:09,122
Yes, well, a man
in a hospital waiting room

1445
01:12:09,200 --> 01:12:10,440
while a loved one
is under the knife

1446
01:12:10,520 --> 01:12:11,965
has many
feverish thoughts.

1447
01:12:12,040 --> 01:12:14,646
I imagined that
if I prayed

1448
01:12:14,720 --> 01:12:16,802
my prayers
might be heard.

1449
01:12:17,280 --> 01:12:19,123
You thought of praying?

1450
01:12:19,200 --> 01:12:22,170
I never imagined
I would hear those words.

1451
01:12:22,240 --> 01:12:25,449
And my ace in the hole,
so to speak, was that...

1452
01:12:25,520 --> 01:12:28,410
Even if the worst had happened and
Aunt Vanessa had sadly passed away,

1453
01:12:28,480 --> 01:12:30,847
you could always put me in touch
with her in the spirit world,

1454
01:12:30,920 --> 01:12:31,967
and that...

1455
01:12:32,520 --> 01:12:34,522
That rather put
a smile on my face.

1456
01:12:34,600 --> 01:12:37,365
Well, in the end,
she pulled through.

1457
01:12:37,440 --> 01:12:39,044
Well, you look exhausted.

1458
01:12:39,120 --> 01:12:40,485
Well, can you blame me?

1459
01:12:40,560 --> 01:12:44,167
What I need now is a good
bath and a nap and...

1460
01:12:44,240 --> 01:12:45,321
So, if you'll excuse me...

1461
01:12:45,400 --> 01:12:46,447
SOPHIE: Yes, of course.

1462
01:12:46,520 --> 01:12:48,249
(LAUGHING)
Stanley...

1463
01:12:49,440 --> 01:12:51,841
Oh, I'm so relieved
about Aunt Vanessa.

1464
01:12:51,920 --> 01:12:54,207
She's such
a marvelous woman.

1465
01:12:54,280 --> 01:12:56,203
Yeah, she's so lovely.

1466
01:12:56,280 --> 01:12:58,009
We should break open
the champagne.

1467
01:12:58,080 --> 01:13:00,287
We should celebrate.

1468
01:13:00,360 --> 01:13:02,203
HOWARD: Aunt Vanessa's
recovered.

1469
01:13:02,280 --> 01:13:05,602
Not to mention that I
find this whole thing

1470
01:13:05,680 --> 01:13:08,206
a most rewarding
experience.

1471
01:13:10,080 --> 01:13:11,844
You feel no remorse?

1472
01:13:13,040 --> 01:13:14,644
Why should
I feel remorse?

1473
01:13:14,720 --> 01:13:17,371
Hoodwinking
a lifelong friend.

1474
01:13:18,480 --> 01:13:19,641
Mmm.

1475
01:13:19,720 --> 01:13:21,006
I see it
quite differently.

1476
01:13:21,080 --> 01:13:23,128
Hoodwinking is what we do.

1477
01:13:24,160 --> 01:13:26,162
Now, you've got to understand
that since we were boys,

1478
01:13:26,240 --> 01:13:28,004
I have played
second fiddle

1479
01:13:28,080 --> 01:13:30,048
to that egomaniacal,
self-regarding...

1480
01:13:30,120 --> 01:13:31,201
Genius.

1481
01:13:31,280 --> 01:13:32,805
HOWARD: Yeah, he's a
genius at what he does,

1482
01:13:32,880 --> 01:13:35,451
and I turned out
to be a mere mortal.

1483
01:13:35,520 --> 01:13:39,081
But now, after years
of trailing in his wake,

1484
01:13:39,160 --> 01:13:41,242
and I admit,
some envy and resentment,

1485
01:13:41,320 --> 01:13:45,723
I have finally put one over
the great Wei Ling Soo.

1486
01:13:45,800 --> 01:13:49,964
I have fooled the man
who could not be fooled.

1487
01:13:50,040 --> 01:13:52,725
Not quite, Howard.

1488
01:13:54,120 --> 01:13:55,201
How did...

1489
01:13:55,280 --> 01:13:58,329
STANLEY: You admired this effect
when you saw my show in Berlin.

1490
01:13:58,400 --> 01:14:00,400
I said I'd teach it to you
if you behaved yourself,

1491
01:14:00,440 --> 01:14:02,681
but you have not behaved.

1492
01:14:03,240 --> 01:14:05,129
It's a trick, Sophie.

1493
01:14:05,200 --> 01:14:08,682
I don't really dematerialize
and reassemble my ectoplasm

1494
01:14:08,760 --> 01:14:12,003
any more than you contact
spirits or read minds.

1495
01:14:12,080 --> 01:14:13,605
Stanley, I can explain...

1496
01:14:13,680 --> 01:14:16,126
I watched you so closely.

1497
01:14:16,200 --> 01:14:18,362
Howard watched your mother,

1498
01:14:18,440 --> 01:14:21,569
but who watched Howard?

1499
01:14:22,840 --> 01:14:24,490
You were free
to rap on the table.

1500
01:14:24,560 --> 01:14:25,527
You seized
the floating candle,

1501
01:14:25,600 --> 01:14:27,807
you swore there were no
wires making it float,

1502
01:14:27,880 --> 01:14:30,645
and I took you
at your word.

1503
01:14:30,720 --> 01:14:32,688
You were free to rap
once for yes, twice for no.

1504
01:14:32,760 --> 01:14:35,570
And when Sophie excused
herself at my aunt's

1505
01:14:35,640 --> 01:14:39,008
to make a telephone call,
she called you

1506
01:14:39,120 --> 01:14:43,125
and you fed her
information about my aunt.

1507
01:14:44,000 --> 01:14:45,001
At first,
I couldn't believe

1508
01:14:45,080 --> 01:14:46,366
you would betray me
like that.

1509
01:14:48,000 --> 01:14:49,889
But, as you know,

1510
01:14:49,960 --> 01:14:52,042
I am a misanthrope.

1511
01:14:52,120 --> 01:14:53,929
And that people do
unconscionable things

1512
01:14:54,000 --> 01:14:57,209
does not run counter to my
normal view of humanity.

1513
01:14:57,280 --> 01:15:00,966
As boys, we both chose
magic as our calling.

1514
01:15:01,040 --> 01:15:04,761
We both practiced day and
night, I as much as you.

1515
01:15:04,840 --> 01:15:07,161
My skill was
the equal of yours,

1516
01:15:07,240 --> 01:15:11,689
and yet, you emerged onto the
world stage as the great artist.

1517
01:15:12,600 --> 01:15:13,840
But it wasn't fair.

1518
01:15:13,920 --> 01:15:16,161
Life's not fair, Howard.

1519
01:15:16,840 --> 01:15:18,842
In fact, as a general
rule, as I've often said,

1520
01:15:18,920 --> 01:15:20,285
it's pretty nasty.

1521
01:15:22,400 --> 01:15:23,925
Because of Sophie,

1522
01:15:24,760 --> 01:15:27,331
I began to succumb
to magical thinking.

1523
01:15:28,600 --> 01:15:31,251
And for a while,
I was actually happy.

1524
01:15:32,720 --> 01:15:34,404
But I was happy
as a fool is happy.

1525
01:15:34,480 --> 01:15:37,245
Happiness is not
the natural human condition.

1526
01:15:37,320 --> 01:15:39,687
And incidentally, you never
practiced as much as I did,

1527
01:15:39,760 --> 01:15:41,489
and your skill
was never equal to mine.

1528
01:15:41,560 --> 01:15:43,005
Stanley, I'm sorry,
I'm sorry...

1529
01:15:43,080 --> 01:15:46,289
I ran into Howard here when he
was sent to expose me, and he...

1530
01:15:46,360 --> 01:15:49,125
He did expose me,
quite easily.

1531
01:15:49,200 --> 01:15:51,202
But we made this private
pact to do this scheme,

1532
01:15:51,280 --> 01:15:55,365
and I only agreed because it
meant so much to Mom and me.

1533
01:15:56,040 --> 01:15:58,805
I view your behavior as

1534
01:15:58,880 --> 01:16:02,282
a great man views
the malicious mischief of...

1535
01:16:02,360 --> 01:16:04,840
What shall we say, pygmy?

1536
01:16:04,920 --> 01:16:06,445
You're a fake.

1537
01:16:06,520 --> 01:16:09,729
As I always should have
known, and did, in my heart.

1538
01:16:09,800 --> 01:16:12,644
I only wish I hadn't wasted
so much time with you.

1539
01:16:13,600 --> 01:16:18,322
Well, now you're just being
a pompous stick in the mud.

1540
01:16:18,400 --> 01:16:20,562
We played an elaborate
joke on you, Stanley.

1541
01:16:20,680 --> 01:16:22,125
No one was harmed.

1542
01:16:22,400 --> 01:16:23,811
My reputation
will suffer,

1543
01:16:23,880 --> 01:16:25,609
and you played me
for a fool.

1544
01:16:25,680 --> 01:16:28,081
Your reputation
is all ego!

1545
01:16:28,160 --> 01:16:29,605
(STAMMERING) I've...

1546
01:16:29,680 --> 01:16:31,523
Yes, yes,
things got out of hand,

1547
01:16:31,600 --> 01:16:33,090
but no awful thing happened.

1548
01:16:33,160 --> 01:16:35,242
I mean, you were...
You were happy.

1549
01:16:35,360 --> 01:16:37,727
And you enjoyed life
for once.

1550
01:16:37,800 --> 01:16:40,610
You saw the world
as optimists see the world.

1551
01:16:40,680 --> 01:16:42,250
And we had some
laughs together,

1552
01:16:42,320 --> 01:16:44,800
so don't say that you wasted
your time with me.

1553
01:16:44,880 --> 01:16:46,530
What would you
have been doing?

1554
01:16:46,600 --> 01:16:50,446
Sitting in your room and shuffling
cards in front of a mirror?

1555
01:16:50,520 --> 01:16:52,602
All my optimism
was an illusion.

1556
01:16:52,680 --> 01:16:54,364
Well, I started
reading that book

1557
01:16:54,440 --> 01:16:56,966
by that German philosopher,
you know, that you gave me?

1558
01:16:57,040 --> 01:16:59,008
I didn't really
understand much of it,

1559
01:16:59,080 --> 01:17:02,129
but he said that we need
our illusions to live.

1560
01:17:02,200 --> 01:17:03,531
You mean lies.

1561
01:17:04,040 --> 01:17:05,087
You were much happier

1562
01:17:05,160 --> 01:17:07,208
when you let some lies
into your life, Stanley.

1563
01:17:07,480 --> 01:17:08,811
HOWARD: Think about it,
Stanley,

1564
01:17:08,880 --> 01:17:11,884
do you really want to ruin the
peace of mind Grace Catledge has,

1565
01:17:11,960 --> 01:17:15,282
secure in the knowledge that she
is her husband's only love?

1566
01:17:15,400 --> 01:17:17,368
We can't go around
deluding ourselves.

1567
01:17:17,440 --> 01:17:19,602
But we must.

1568
01:17:19,680 --> 01:17:22,126
If we're to
get through life.

1569
01:17:22,240 --> 01:17:24,288
I mean, I didn't say it,

1570
01:17:24,360 --> 01:17:26,567
I'm just quoting,
you know, Mister...

1571
01:17:26,880 --> 01:17:28,086
Um...

1572
01:17:28,480 --> 01:17:29,561
Nietzsche.

1573
01:17:29,640 --> 01:17:33,008
And, in the end, who really knows
what's real and what's not?

1574
01:17:33,080 --> 01:17:35,970
Well, it's quite clear what's real,
my praying for my aunt was poppycock,

1575
01:17:36,040 --> 01:17:37,644
the doctor's skill
was real.

1576
01:17:37,720 --> 01:17:40,485
No. You will never
know that, because George,

1577
01:17:40,560 --> 01:17:43,370
Caroline's husband,
the psychoanalyst,

1578
01:17:43,440 --> 01:17:45,841
told me that he was praying
for your aunt, too.

1579
01:17:45,920 --> 01:17:47,285
And so we don't know
if maybe

1580
01:17:47,360 --> 01:17:49,488
it was his prayers
that got answered.

1581
01:17:49,600 --> 01:17:51,409
Maybe the angels
like him better.

1582
01:17:51,760 --> 01:17:54,843
I won't dignify this
conversation any longer.

1583
01:17:54,920 --> 01:17:56,445
I'm going to go
and visit my Aunt Vanessa

1584
01:17:56,520 --> 01:17:59,364
until she's on her feet,
and then good-bye.

1585
01:17:59,440 --> 01:18:01,488
And you won't forgive me?

1586
01:18:01,560 --> 01:18:03,369
Well, I can't forgive you.

1587
01:18:03,440 --> 01:18:05,807
Only God can forgive you.

1588
01:18:05,880 --> 01:18:07,848
But you said
there is no God.

1589
01:18:09,000 --> 01:18:11,082
Precisely my point.

1590
01:18:13,560 --> 01:18:15,324
(♪♪♪)

1591
01:18:27,280 --> 01:18:32,810
<i>♪ Lovers depend on
moonlight for</i> a <i>love affair</i>

1592
01:18:33,520 --> 01:18:38,970
<i>♪ Babies depend on mothers
for their tender care</i>

1593
01:18:39,720 --> 01:18:44,965
<i>♪ Flowers depend on sunshine
and the morning dew</i>

1594
01:18:45,960 --> 01:18:48,804
<i>♪ Each thing depends
on something</i>

1595
01:18:48,880 --> 01:18:52,202
<i>♪ And I depend on you</i>

1596
01:18:53,400 --> 01:18:56,643
<i>♪ I can be happy,
I can be sad</i>

1597
01:18:56,720 --> 01:18:59,246
<i>♪ I can be good,
I can be bad</i>

1598
01:18:59,320 --> 01:19:03,166
<i>♪ It all depends on you</i>

1599
01:19:05,120 --> 01:19:07,771
<i>♪ I can be lonely
out in</i> a <i>crowd</i>

1600
01:19:07,840 --> 01:19:08,921
<i>♪ I can be humble ♪</i>

1601
01:19:09,000 --> 01:19:10,411
VANESSA: Oh, it's good
to be home.

1602
01:19:10,480 --> 01:19:13,450
More robust than ever,
I'll wager.

1603
01:19:13,560 --> 01:19:16,643
"What doesn't kill me
makes me stronger."

1604
01:19:16,720 --> 01:19:18,245
A great man said that.

1605
01:19:18,320 --> 01:19:19,924
Oh, not
the "God is dead" fellow.

1606
01:19:20,000 --> 01:19:21,126
STANLEY: The very same.

1607
01:19:21,200 --> 01:19:22,770
Nevertheless,
I think he was wrong.

1608
01:19:22,840 --> 01:19:24,842
What doesn't kill us often
knocks the hell out of us.

1609
01:19:24,920 --> 01:19:28,242
Well, sometimes a close
call wakes a person up.

1610
01:19:30,000 --> 01:19:31,923
I've had another idea
for our honeymoon.

1611
01:19:32,000 --> 01:19:33,968
What if,
after the Greek Islands,

1612
01:19:34,080 --> 01:19:35,730
we set sail
for the South Seas.

1613
01:19:35,800 --> 01:19:37,848
I've always wanted
to visit Bora Bora.

1614
01:19:37,960 --> 01:19:39,291
Would that interest you?

1615
01:19:39,360 --> 01:19:41,010
I've never...
I've never heard of it,

1616
01:19:41,080 --> 01:19:43,651
but the name
sounds pretty exotic.

1617
01:19:43,760 --> 01:19:45,728
Exotic?
Mmm-hmm.

1618
01:19:46,360 --> 01:19:49,204
BRICE: I love how you pick
always the exact right word.

1619
01:19:50,240 --> 01:19:51,241
(LAUGHS)

1620
01:19:52,120 --> 01:19:53,485
Yes, of course, Olivia.

1621
01:19:53,600 --> 01:19:55,443
I'll be home
in a few days.

1622
01:19:55,560 --> 01:19:58,006
I just have to see that Aunt
Vanessa is up and running,

1623
01:19:58,080 --> 01:20:00,970
and, uh, I have one or two
press interviews I have to do.

1624
01:20:01,040 --> 01:20:02,963
Some things need to be
smoothed over.

1625
01:20:03,040 --> 01:20:05,168
This is where
I could use your tact.

1626
01:20:05,240 --> 01:20:07,607
Yes, of course. Yes.

1627
01:20:07,680 --> 01:20:09,250
Bye, darling.

1628
01:20:11,000 --> 01:20:12,968
I bet you'll be glad
to get back to London

1629
01:20:13,040 --> 01:20:14,769
and put all this
behind you.

1630
01:20:14,840 --> 01:20:15,966
Um...

1631
01:20:17,280 --> 01:20:20,329
You might enjoy
the Galapagos.

1632
01:20:20,400 --> 01:20:22,129
You're a great admirer
of Darwin's.

1633
01:20:22,200 --> 01:20:25,249
Big turtles.
Yes, I suppose so.

1634
01:20:26,960 --> 01:20:29,804
And of course,
you must miss Olivia.

1635
01:20:29,880 --> 01:20:30,961
Um...

1636
01:20:33,640 --> 01:20:37,326
A very fine woman. I can tell
that from her photographs.

1637
01:20:37,400 --> 01:20:39,164
Such elegance and style.

1638
01:20:39,240 --> 01:20:41,846
Absolutely perfect
for a man of your taste.

1639
01:20:41,920 --> 01:20:44,127
Well, yes, it's...
There's no question.

1640
01:20:44,200 --> 01:20:46,680
We're ideally suited.

1641
01:20:46,760 --> 01:20:50,162
A very... And you need
a well-educated woman

1642
01:20:50,280 --> 01:20:52,362
to keep up with you.

1643
01:20:53,400 --> 01:20:55,289
And she's quite
attractive, to boot.

1644
01:20:55,360 --> 01:20:58,648
Yes, yes,
it's very easy to see us

1645
01:20:58,720 --> 01:21:01,326
side by side
through life's journey.

1646
01:21:01,400 --> 01:21:04,529
A very handsome
couple indeed.

1647
01:21:04,600 --> 01:21:07,331
Yes, there's no question.
We're ideally suited.

1648
01:21:07,400 --> 01:21:09,243
As you would say.

1649
01:21:09,320 --> 01:21:12,483
A quite rational choice.

1650
01:21:12,560 --> 01:21:15,404
I mean, it's not
entirely cerebral.

1651
01:21:15,480 --> 01:21:17,482
I mean, I do love her.

1652
01:21:17,600 --> 01:21:18,965
What are you suggesting?

1653
01:21:19,080 --> 01:21:22,209
Suggesting? In the
nuance of your tone?

1654
01:21:22,280 --> 01:21:24,123
Of course I love her.

1655
01:21:24,200 --> 01:21:26,043
Or are you saying

1656
01:21:26,120 --> 01:21:28,122
you think I've come to
love Sophie Baker?

1657
01:21:28,200 --> 01:21:30,567
Me? I never
mentioned Sophie.

1658
01:21:30,640 --> 01:21:32,290
Well, I thought you
were heading there.

1659
01:21:32,360 --> 01:21:33,521
Sophie Baker?

1660
01:21:33,600 --> 01:21:34,886
The little fake who
played you for a dupe?

1661
01:21:34,960 --> 01:21:36,564
Exactly. That wretch.

1662
01:21:36,640 --> 01:21:38,563
Why would I suggest you've
fallen in love with Sophie?

1663
01:21:38,640 --> 01:21:40,085
Well, you might.

1664
01:21:40,160 --> 01:21:41,207
I never know
what goes on

1665
01:21:41,280 --> 01:21:42,566
in that devious mind
of yours.

1666
01:21:42,640 --> 01:21:47,441
The very idea of you and that
specious American telepathic.

1667
01:21:47,520 --> 01:21:49,807
Well, I know
it defies all reason.

1668
01:21:49,880 --> 01:21:53,407
You, a creature of reason.
A man of intellect.

1669
01:21:53,480 --> 01:21:54,686
To be sure.

1670
01:21:54,760 --> 01:21:56,091
VANESSA: Certainly
not trivial.

1671
01:21:56,160 --> 01:21:57,730
No, to say the least.

1672
01:21:57,800 --> 01:22:00,326
And she's hardly in the
same class as Olivia.

1673
01:22:01,000 --> 01:22:03,207
The comparison
makes me laugh.

1674
01:22:03,280 --> 01:22:05,726
Olivia is a person
of accomplishment and charm.

1675
01:22:05,800 --> 01:22:07,086
Sophie's a street finagler

1676
01:22:07,160 --> 01:22:10,130
who makes her way living off
one bit of hokum to the next.

1677
01:22:10,200 --> 01:22:12,328
Well, I don't see how you
can compare the two.

1678
01:22:12,400 --> 01:22:14,971
Well, don't put ideas
into my head!

1679
01:22:15,040 --> 01:22:17,042
Well, far be it from me.

1680
01:22:23,360 --> 01:22:26,011
Of course, she does come
from dire circumstances.

1681
01:22:26,080 --> 01:22:28,447
I mean, it's very
easy to be judgmental

1682
01:22:28,520 --> 01:22:30,602
about people who are
born into circumstances

1683
01:22:30,680 --> 01:22:32,648
less fortunate
than one's own.

1684
01:22:32,760 --> 01:22:34,125
Life is harsh.

1685
01:22:34,200 --> 01:22:36,487
One must do what one
must to survive.

1686
01:22:36,560 --> 01:22:37,800
STANLEY: Well put.

1687
01:22:37,880 --> 01:22:39,848
And people do sometimes
make the wrong choices,

1688
01:22:39,920 --> 01:22:41,843
which they regret,

1689
01:22:41,920 --> 01:22:45,641
even though no serious
harm was done.

1690
01:22:45,720 --> 01:22:48,326
Which of us has not made
some blunders in life?

1691
01:22:48,440 --> 01:22:52,126
And there is a rather appealing
quality about Sophie.

1692
01:22:52,200 --> 01:22:54,168
Despite her
disgusting behavior.

1693
01:22:54,280 --> 01:22:58,808
Yes, her smile
is rather winning.

1694
01:22:58,880 --> 01:23:00,325
Of course, it depends
how much value

1695
01:23:00,400 --> 01:23:01,845
you put
on the purely physical.

1696
01:23:01,920 --> 01:23:03,649
STANLEY: Well, no, l...

1697
01:23:03,720 --> 01:23:05,688
I, for one,
esteem the higher virtues.

1698
01:23:05,760 --> 01:23:06,807
Hmm...

1699
01:23:06,880 --> 01:23:08,928
Beauty of the soul.

1700
01:23:11,560 --> 01:23:14,882
Although her eyes are rather
pleasant to look into.

1701
01:23:15,560 --> 01:23:17,881
And that she can be amusing,
under the right circumstances.

1702
01:23:17,960 --> 01:23:21,521
Oh, but Olivia is an
educated, cultivated woman.

1703
01:23:21,640 --> 01:23:24,246
One that befits a man
of your artistic genius.

1704
01:23:24,320 --> 01:23:27,051
Yes, now, my genius
must be factored in.

1705
01:23:27,120 --> 01:23:29,009
On paper,
there's really no reason

1706
01:23:29,080 --> 01:23:31,845
to prefer
Sophie to Olivia.

1707
01:23:31,920 --> 01:23:33,763
Well, I would say
the opposite.

1708
01:23:35,560 --> 01:23:37,927
(STAMMERING) And so
your suggestion that I,

1709
01:23:38,000 --> 01:23:39,684
I be honest with Olivia

1710
01:23:39,760 --> 01:23:42,684
and tell her that
irrational as it seems,

1711
01:23:42,760 --> 01:23:45,161
I've fallen in
love with Sophie,

1712
01:23:45,240 --> 01:23:47,766
that's a
preposterous notion.

1713
01:23:47,840 --> 01:23:49,922
It's lunacy.

1714
01:23:52,960 --> 01:23:54,405
Yet I can't help
feeling that...

1715
01:23:54,480 --> 01:23:57,165
That you love Sophie.

1716
01:23:57,240 --> 01:23:58,730
Yes, I understand.

1717
01:23:58,800 --> 01:24:00,609
You're puzzled
and bewildered

1718
01:24:00,720 --> 01:24:02,529
because your foolish logic

1719
01:24:02,640 --> 01:24:05,325
Tells you that
you should love Olivia.

1720
01:24:05,400 --> 01:24:06,686
Foolish logic?

1721
01:24:06,760 --> 01:24:09,240
And yet, how little
that logic means

1722
01:24:09,320 --> 01:24:12,085
when placed
next to Sophie's smile.

1723
01:24:12,160 --> 01:24:13,924
What are you saying?

1724
01:24:15,200 --> 01:24:18,921
That the world may or may
not be without purpose,

1725
01:24:19,000 --> 01:24:22,721
but it's not totally without
some kind of magic.

1726
01:24:24,720 --> 01:24:27,644
I have irrational positive
feelings for Sophie Baker.

1727
01:24:29,240 --> 01:24:31,561
It's like witnessing
a trick I can't figure out.

1728
01:24:31,640 --> 01:24:34,325
I wouldn't try to figure it out.
I'd simply move on it.

1729
01:24:34,400 --> 01:24:38,041
Word is, she's already accepted
Brice Catledge's proposal.

1730
01:24:56,720 --> 01:24:59,485
Taken to reading
the great books?

1731
01:25:01,360 --> 01:25:02,725
Yes.

1732
01:25:03,600 --> 01:25:06,922
Well, you once said
not to despair.

1733
01:25:07,000 --> 01:25:08,843
There's hope
for my brain.

1734
01:25:09,680 --> 01:25:12,286
Perhaps I was
a bit caustic.

1735
01:25:12,360 --> 01:25:13,441
But you will
admit you were guilty

1736
01:25:13,520 --> 01:25:16,285
of some rather
sleazy doings.

1737
01:25:17,200 --> 01:25:19,282
Yes, well,
those days are over.

1738
01:25:19,360 --> 01:25:21,601
I no longer
have to worry about

1739
01:25:21,720 --> 01:25:25,122
where to sleep
and how to eat.

1740
01:25:25,200 --> 01:25:28,647
I take it Brice Catledge has made
a serious marriage proposal?

1741
01:25:29,400 --> 01:25:30,845
Yes.

1742
01:25:30,920 --> 01:25:32,649
A very tempting one.

1743
01:25:32,720 --> 01:25:34,131
SOPHIE: Wouldn't you agree?

1744
01:25:34,200 --> 01:25:36,487
Yes, I suppose so.

1745
01:25:36,560 --> 01:25:39,006
But I'm here to make you
a more tempting one.

1746
01:25:39,840 --> 01:25:41,365
More tempting than this?

1747
01:25:42,880 --> 01:25:44,325
I came to say

1748
01:25:44,400 --> 01:25:46,004
that for some
inexplicable reason

1749
01:25:46,080 --> 01:25:49,402
that defies common sense
and human understanding,

1750
01:25:50,520 --> 01:25:52,602
that I have, of late,

1751
01:25:52,680 --> 01:25:54,603
experienced some small...

1752
01:25:54,680 --> 01:25:57,445
Quite small,
but discernible

1753
01:25:57,520 --> 01:26:00,171
inner stirrings
regarding your smile.

1754
01:26:00,720 --> 01:26:02,085
How magnanimous of you.

1755
01:26:02,160 --> 01:26:03,924
STANLEY: Yes,
I thought you'd think so.

1756
01:26:04,000 --> 01:26:06,241
And possessing
a soul which is large

1757
01:26:06,320 --> 01:26:09,608
and capable of complexity,
as all great minds are,

1758
01:26:09,680 --> 01:26:11,728
I have decided
to forgive you

1759
01:26:11,800 --> 01:26:14,087
and take you
under my wing.

1760
01:26:15,200 --> 01:26:16,884
Your wing?

1761
01:26:17,560 --> 01:26:20,006
It's a saying. Obviously,
I don't have wings.

1762
01:26:20,080 --> 01:26:22,560
I only mean that,

1763
01:26:22,640 --> 01:26:24,005
incredible as it sounds,

1764
01:26:24,080 --> 01:26:26,321
and this is no small gesture,
given the time wasted

1765
01:26:26,400 --> 01:26:28,289
and the public embarrassment
you've caused me,

1766
01:26:28,360 --> 01:26:30,647
that I'm

1767
01:26:30,720 --> 01:26:32,722
willing to
take you back.

1768
01:26:33,280 --> 01:26:34,884
Take me back where?

1769
01:26:35,720 --> 01:26:38,291
Under the moon
in the observatory.

1770
01:26:38,760 --> 01:26:42,401
I regretted
what I was doing,

1771
01:26:42,480 --> 01:26:44,323
but I was too inept
to change course,

1772
01:26:44,400 --> 01:26:48,200
and I apologize.

1773
01:26:48,280 --> 01:26:49,611
Really.

1774
01:26:49,680 --> 01:26:50,841
And I accept
your forgiveness.

1775
01:26:50,920 --> 01:26:53,002
I understand that
it's very generous of you,

1776
01:26:53,080 --> 01:26:54,684
and I have to be going.

1777
01:26:54,760 --> 01:26:57,366
Going? I haven't said
what I came for.

1778
01:26:57,480 --> 01:26:59,209
Well, then just
say it and go,

1779
01:26:59,280 --> 01:27:01,806
because I have a dinner
to go to with my fiancé.

1780
01:27:02,800 --> 01:27:04,882
I'm here to say

1781
01:27:04,960 --> 01:27:07,327
that in spite of everything,

1782
01:27:07,400 --> 01:27:09,926
l am willing to
consider marrying you.

1783
01:27:10,520 --> 01:27:12,090
What?
Naturally,

1784
01:27:12,160 --> 01:27:15,642
you can't believe your good fortune.
I appreciate that.

1785
01:27:16,520 --> 01:27:19,205
Stanley, brilliant as you
are with a deck of cards,

1786
01:27:19,280 --> 01:27:22,841
you are terrible
at proposing.

1787
01:27:24,160 --> 01:27:25,286
I've never
proposed before.

1788
01:27:25,360 --> 01:27:26,407
SOPHIE: Oh, really?

1789
01:27:26,480 --> 01:27:28,482
Not even
to your fiancée?

1790
01:27:29,000 --> 01:27:31,241
She proposed marriage.

1791
01:27:31,320 --> 01:27:34,290
The truth is I've never really
felt the urge to propose before.

1792
01:27:34,360 --> 01:27:35,691
SOPHIE: Use your head!

1793
01:27:35,760 --> 01:27:38,491
We're not a match
made in heaven,

1794
01:27:38,560 --> 01:27:41,848
and as you've said
before many times,

1795
01:27:41,920 --> 01:27:44,844
when the heart rules the
head, disaster follows.

1796
01:27:45,400 --> 01:27:47,767
But the fact is

1797
01:27:47,840 --> 01:27:50,081
I love you.

1798
01:27:50,200 --> 01:27:52,680
And somewhere
in your confused,

1799
01:27:52,760 --> 01:27:53,960
black, little
criminal's heart,

1800
01:27:54,000 --> 01:27:55,525
you care for me.

1801
01:27:55,880 --> 01:27:58,121
I'm marrying
Brice Catledge.

1802
01:27:58,200 --> 01:27:59,929
You advised me to.

1803
01:28:00,000 --> 01:28:01,604
You must never
take my advice.

1804
01:28:01,680 --> 01:28:02,680
I'm a major eccentric.

1805
01:28:02,720 --> 01:28:04,131
You know,
Brice adores me,

1806
01:28:04,200 --> 01:28:07,409
and he offers me
a life of travel

1807
01:28:07,480 --> 01:28:09,164
and excitement
and high living.

1808
01:28:09,240 --> 01:28:10,241
No, no,

1809
01:28:10,360 --> 01:28:12,400
he worships you, and you
don't want to be worshiped.

1810
01:28:12,440 --> 01:28:13,680
You'll be bored.

1811
01:28:13,760 --> 01:28:15,683
Oh. Sailing to
the Greek Islands?

1812
01:28:15,760 --> 01:28:17,205
And Bora Bora?

1813
01:28:17,280 --> 01:28:19,320
Well, they're just, they're
just rocks in the ocean!

1814
01:28:19,360 --> 01:28:20,930
It's who you go with!

1815
01:28:21,000 --> 01:28:22,889
Do you want to spend the
rest of your life with a man

1816
01:28:22,960 --> 01:28:26,328
who plays the ukulele
and croons to you?

1817
01:28:26,400 --> 01:28:28,801
You know I like you
very much, Stanley.

1818
01:28:29,680 --> 01:28:32,650
I even began
falling in love with you.

1819
01:28:33,960 --> 01:28:38,284
But when you went on to show
me how irrational it was,

1820
01:28:38,360 --> 01:28:40,169
and then you proved it

1821
01:28:40,240 --> 01:28:42,208
with geometrical logic.
No.

1822
01:28:42,280 --> 01:28:44,647
Geometry was never
my strong subject.

1823
01:28:44,720 --> 01:28:47,485
After all,
what can you offer me?

1824
01:28:47,560 --> 01:28:49,130
Grumpy moods?

1825
01:28:49,200 --> 01:28:50,804
Insults?

1826
01:28:50,880 --> 01:28:52,370
Pessimistic grumbling

1827
01:28:52,440 --> 01:28:55,649
about how awful life is
for all of us?

1828
01:28:55,720 --> 01:28:57,484
Well, around you,
I'm not gloomy.

1829
01:28:57,600 --> 01:28:59,523
That's only
because I fooled you

1830
01:28:59,600 --> 01:29:02,444
into thinking that there's more
to life than meets the eye.

1831
01:29:02,520 --> 01:29:05,205
No, no, I have not
lost my pessimism,

1832
01:29:05,280 --> 01:29:10,002
but you are like an oasis
in the grim desert.

1833
01:29:10,080 --> 01:29:12,651
And as far as
what I can offer you,

1834
01:29:12,720 --> 01:29:15,724
life with a brilliant
and witty genius.

1835
01:29:17,280 --> 01:29:18,280
I have to go.

1836
01:29:18,320 --> 01:29:20,084
No, this is
your last offer.

1837
01:29:20,160 --> 01:29:21,685
You must not
be an ingrate.

1838
01:29:21,760 --> 01:29:22,841
Good-bye, Stanley.

1839
01:29:22,960 --> 01:29:25,201
I will not stand around
here, cap in hand,

1840
01:29:25,280 --> 01:29:28,648
waiting for some halfpenny
con artist to be my bride!

1841
01:29:29,440 --> 01:29:30,771
This is it.
You don't agree now,

1842
01:29:30,840 --> 01:29:32,808
offer's off the table.

1843
01:29:32,880 --> 01:29:34,041
Do you hear me?

1844
01:29:34,120 --> 01:29:35,804
You irritating Lilliputian!

1845
01:29:35,880 --> 01:29:38,804
You're throwing away
your passport to paradise!

1846
01:29:40,440 --> 01:29:42,204
Can you
forgive me, Stanley?

1847
01:29:42,280 --> 01:29:44,248
Oh, I have forgiven you,
Howard,

1848
01:29:44,320 --> 01:29:46,322
as I've forgiven Sophie.

1849
01:29:46,440 --> 01:29:49,205
I agree, I needed
a pie in the face.

1850
01:29:49,320 --> 01:29:51,560
Well, I saw a side of you in
this I've never seen before.

1851
01:29:51,600 --> 01:29:53,841
It was refreshing.

1852
01:29:53,920 --> 01:29:57,242
Even now, Sophie's smile
still penetrates my soul.

1853
01:29:57,320 --> 01:30:00,290
(SCOFFS) Now you believe
we have souls?

1854
01:30:00,360 --> 01:30:04,251
No, I believe each of us must find
a reason to truly embrace life,

1855
01:30:04,320 --> 01:30:06,891
and for me,
Sophie is that reason.

1856
01:30:06,960 --> 01:30:09,531
Well, if nothing else,
it's made you certain

1857
01:30:09,600 --> 01:30:11,967
it would've been
a mistake to marry Olivia.

1858
01:30:12,040 --> 01:30:14,202
I spoke to Olivia
on the telephone.

1859
01:30:14,280 --> 01:30:16,567
She's much less upset
than I'd anticipated.

1860
01:30:16,680 --> 01:30:20,241
Very calm,
very reasonable.

1861
01:30:20,320 --> 01:30:21,845
She's in the Galapagos.

1862
01:30:21,920 --> 01:30:24,241
She said
she was disappointed,

1863
01:30:24,320 --> 01:30:26,607
but she understood that
these things happen,

1864
01:30:26,680 --> 01:30:29,445
and if I was still going to
feel this way when I returned,

1865
01:30:29,520 --> 01:30:31,522
it's much better
we found out now.

1866
01:30:31,600 --> 01:30:33,887
What a lovely,
rational human being.

1867
01:30:33,960 --> 01:30:35,405
I should look her up.

1868
01:30:35,480 --> 01:30:38,370
She's bright, pretty,
she likes magicians.

1869
01:30:38,800 --> 01:30:39,801
(♪♪♪)

1870
01:31:17,560 --> 01:31:19,801
Well, how did it go?

1871
01:31:19,880 --> 01:31:22,247
Can you believe
she turned me down?

1872
01:31:22,400 --> 01:31:23,447
Oh.

1873
01:31:23,520 --> 01:31:25,409
Poor Stanley.

1874
01:31:25,760 --> 01:31:28,331
That scamp
could've had me,

1875
01:31:28,400 --> 01:31:31,051
but instead,
she chose Brice Catledge.

1876
01:31:31,120 --> 01:31:34,488
Well, he is very rich
and good-looking.

1877
01:31:34,560 --> 01:31:35,925
She'd have been
happier with me.

1878
01:31:36,000 --> 01:31:38,731
So in the end,
you lost her.

1879
01:31:38,800 --> 01:31:41,246
It's sad, because

1880
01:31:41,320 --> 01:31:43,561
there really was
something between us.

1881
01:31:44,680 --> 01:31:48,048
Some chemistry.
Some magic.

1882
01:31:48,120 --> 01:31:51,681
And I say chemistry
or magic because...

1883
01:31:51,760 --> 01:31:54,843
I believe I actually
loved her from the first,

1884
01:31:54,920 --> 01:31:56,888
first moment
I laid eyes on her.

1885
01:31:56,960 --> 01:32:00,203
Well, love at first sight is
a kind of magic, isn't it?

1886
01:32:00,280 --> 01:32:02,203
You need a drink.
What will you have?

1887
01:32:02,280 --> 01:32:03,566
A scotch, please.

1888
01:32:04,920 --> 01:32:06,922
In the end,
she proved to be a fool.

1889
01:32:07,040 --> 01:32:10,089
You mean to choose that handsome
young millionaire over you?

1890
01:32:10,160 --> 01:32:12,401
VANESSA: Well, she may
come to her senses.

1891
01:32:12,480 --> 01:32:15,609
Women do change their mind
about such things.

1892
01:32:15,680 --> 01:32:18,490
Well, it's too late... I've
taken the offer off the table.

1893
01:32:18,560 --> 01:32:21,040
I'll not let myself be
pushed around by big eyes

1894
01:32:21,120 --> 01:32:23,327
and a smile.

1895
01:32:25,600 --> 01:32:27,602
Although she's much more.

1896
01:32:29,080 --> 01:32:31,082
But she had her chance,
and she said no.

1897
01:32:31,160 --> 01:32:34,687
You mean if she changed her
mind, you wouldn't accept her?

1898
01:32:34,760 --> 01:32:36,000
It's too late.

1899
01:32:36,080 --> 01:32:38,082
Oh, you can't be
that stubborn.

1900
01:32:40,960 --> 01:32:45,249
Well, l suppose if she woke
up and realized how happy

1901
01:32:45,320 --> 01:32:46,685
she'd be with me,

1902
01:32:46,760 --> 01:32:49,161
how much more fun
she'd have in life,

1903
01:32:50,560 --> 01:32:52,642
how much
I'd come to love her.

1904
01:32:53,480 --> 01:32:55,244
She gave nothing back.

1905
01:32:55,320 --> 01:32:58,244
She gave you no sign
at all that she cared?

1906
01:32:59,960 --> 01:33:03,169
If she'd given me a sign,

1907
01:33:03,240 --> 01:33:06,801
I'd have taken her
in my arms, carried her off

1908
01:33:06,880 --> 01:33:08,882
and married her.

1909
01:33:10,320 --> 01:33:13,210
All I was looking for
was one sign.

1910
01:33:17,360 --> 01:33:18,361
(THUMPS ONCE)

1911
01:33:21,880 --> 01:33:23,530
Sophie?

1912
01:33:26,360 --> 01:33:27,361
(THUMPS ONCE)

1913
01:33:31,240 --> 01:33:32,890
Will you marry me?

1914
01:33:36,480 --> 01:33:37,481
(THUMPS ONCE)

1915
01:33:40,040 --> 01:33:41,326
(LAUGHS QUIETLY)

1916
01:33:41,400 --> 01:33:42,890
(♪♪♪)

